INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (624, 9, '2009-11-13 05:17:28', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/brandx-banking-tokyo.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-632" title="brandx-banking-tokyo-thumb" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/brandx-banking-tokyo-thumb.png" alt="brandx-banking-tokyo-thumb" width="278" height="135" /></a>\r\n\r\nPocket Aces Bank wins huge pots with the best hands and loses the very minimum with second best, but sometimes it’s hard to know what arsenal their opponents have and how they are playing. Staying ahead of the game as usual, Pocket Aces looks for the best tools to analyze any situation. Nimbly responding to market trends is the case in this situation.\r\n\r\nGenerally, Pocket Aces is good with stacking up chips but occasionally runs into some difficulties with branch siting and formatting. As a solution, Pocket Aces plays smart and frugally uses its chips to purchase information (data) to locate their target segment rather than try to bluff out the competition. Sticking to its game by trusting its own bank data in combination with accessing up-to-date market data to accurately read its opponents has consistently placed Pocket Aces in the top money finishes.\r\n\r\n<a title="Reduce the risk of expanding and optimizing in emerging markets." href="http://www.getchee.com/about/about-index.html" target="_blank">Learn about Pocket Aces’s secret weapon, <em>getchee</em> Enterprise™, now!</a>', 'Brand X – Banking Edition', 0, '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2009-11-13 05:17:28', '2009-11-13 09:17:28', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=624', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (687, 9, '2009-11-26 22:09:39', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Mr. Chang steps out of his car and runs into the local mobile phone shop to pick up his brand new jailbroken iPhone 3GS. Big smile on his face, he jumps back into his car and pops a random SIM card into his new status symbol. Relaxing to a rigorous foot massage, Mr. Chang fumbles around with a couple of the iPhone’s apps, particularly QQ’s (China’s largest social networking site). He pulls out a wad of cash to pay for the massage and rides off in his car to a dinner meeting. It’s 7:30 p.m. and Chang is the first to arrive at the 7 p.m. gathering. He throws his LV wallet and iPhone on the table and waits for the rest of the crowd to show up. Everyone else starts rolling in around 7:45 p.m. and they begin the ritual of exchanging business cards with two hands. A lot of whiskey and a few hours later, the guanxi (relations) between everyone is tighter and Chang is ready for the next venue to ponder the rest of the mounting business deal. He hops into the luxurious back seat of his Buick, flips to CCTV, and tells his driver to take him to the hostess bar across town.\r\n\r\n<strong>Key #1: Understanding the Culture</strong>\r\n\r\n- Chinese people don’t like being tied down to a phone contract since they like changing phones often. This is one reason why Apple’s iPhone has had poor success in China and not because of its high price. There are more than 2 million cracked iPhones in China and as many as 3.5 million have owned one.\r\n\r\n- Today in Asia, the people are what they wear and what they have. It is a way of defining their social status. Asians love luxury brands. Walk around Shanghai and you’ll find many men sporting an Omega watch as the brand controls 70% of China’s luxury men’s watch market. Meanwhile, many women tote their authentic and fake Chanel, Gucci, and LV bags with pride.\r\n\r\n- Chinese people aren’t really all that different than anybody else in the world. They still want to ‘belong’ to a part of something but through avenues like QQ and not Facebook or Twitter.\r\n\r\n- Bosses and executives of businesses tend to have a driver. GM realized this and boosted its China sales 25 percent by adapting and manufacturing a car with a luxurious back seat that focuses attention on the person who paid for the car.\r\n\r\n<strong>Key #2: Tweaking Your Business Operations</strong>\r\n\r\n- Hire local talent because it’s the quickest way to know what local people prefer (like luxurious back seats in cars)\r\n\r\n- China is a nation of showing face and building close relationships. Coca-cola has experienced this since they entered the market in the late 1970’s. Coca-cola wasn’t able to gain ground in China until the 1980’s when they gave up ownership of the bottling plants to the government for better sales and distribution rights. Now Coca-cola is looking to double its annual sales from USD$100 billion to $200 billion with the help of 1.3 billion thirsty Chinese consumers.', 'Keys to Marketing Success in China', 0, '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2009-11-26 22:09:39', '2009-11-27 02:09:39', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=687', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (665, 9, '2010-11-15 01:52:58', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '1. There are about 769 million employed people in China.\n\nWhy do I care? Many of these people, single and married, <a title="Many Asians live with their parents until they get married." href="http://www.asian-central.com/stuffasianpeoplelike/2008/07/23/83-not-moving-out/" target="_blank">live together with their families</a> and have money to spend. They are brand conscious and <a title="Asia\'s Love for Luxury Brands" href="http://www.entrepreneur.com/tradejournals/article/164421461.html" target="_blank">willing to spend on these brands</a> (beware of imitations).\n\nNow what? Gear advertising and marketing efforts towards this demographic.\n\nHow do I market to this demographic? If you’re not selling bottled water or vitamins, then you better ensure your brand symbolizes status.\n\n2. China is such a new market that you need to spend tons of effort educating and engaging the consumer about your brand.\n\nWhy do I care? The market is there but you need to figure out if the demand is worth the money you need to spend in order to educate the consumer about your brand or product.\n\nNow what? Learn from other companies that have successfully and unsuccessfully marketed China.\n\nWho has done a good job at avoiding pitfalls when marketing to the Chinese consumer? <a title="Volkswagen in China" href="http://www.ashoksom.com/12-VW_Olympic_Program_in_China.pdf" target="_blank">Volkswagen</a> (VW) has been a marketing chameleon in China since 1985, understanding what the consumer wants and also using its connections to strategically strengthen its brand even though changing times. For you FMCG people out there, PepsiCo’s Doritos brand has definitely stepped up its <a title="Doritos in China: What’s in a (re)brand name?" href="http://enovatechina.com/blog/?p=940" target="_blank">marketing efforts in China</a>. Time, however, will tell whether these efforts are effective or not.\n\n3. Consumers are about <a title="Knockoff Cellphones a Hit in China" href="http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/28/technology/28cell.html?_r=2&amp;scp=1&amp;sq=China%20knock%20off&amp;st=cse" target="_blank">replicas versus real</a>. Ahem…remember those imitations?\n\nWhy do I care? The consumer might like your product but your price point is too high or there might already be a copycat of your product. The consumer might want to support the local economy by purchasing from the neighborhood store or factory.\n\nNow what? Resort to guerilla marketing and show how your product is superior and won’t harm the consumer or the environment. Promote the ‘you get what you pay for’ attitude. Trust me, the Chinese DO believe in <a title="You Get What You Pay for - Chinese Version" href="http://chineseculture.about.com/b/2009/10/23/you-get-what-you-pay-for.htm" target="_blank">this</a> too.\n\nWhy will this work? The recent rise in wealthy Chinese has spawned a small boom in demand for luxury brands. Developing a culture of luxury as the Chinese grow richer and their brand awareness matures will aid the rise of luxury brands in the long run.\n\n4. It’s all about localization; <a title="Who is Jay Chou?" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_chou" target="_blank">Jay Chou</a> over Johnny Depp.\n\nWhy do I care? Even though Johnny Deep is the ‘Sexiest Man Alive’ for the second time he wouldn’t be able to sing his way out of a Maersk cargo ship calamity with a Chinese song. On the other hand, Jay Chou could probably induce a whole crew of Chinese pirates to eat stinky tofu off of his piano.\n\nNow what?  Stick to who’s hot and stay away from who’s not.\n\nFood for thought: Chinese people aren’t really all that different than anybody else in the world. They still want to ‘belong’ to a part of something but through avenues like <a title="QQ, China’s Largest Social Networking Site, Raking in the Dough" href="http://www.psfk.com/2008/03/qq-chinas-largest-social-networking-site-raking-in-the-dough.html" target="_blank">QQ</a> and not Facebook or Twitter.', '4 Facts Retail Brands Must Realize When Marketing to China', 0, '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2010-11-15 01:52:58', '2010-11-15 05:52:58', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=665', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2468, 12, '2011-06-30 22:50:20', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Taking effect today, foreign workers in living and working in mainland China will receive medical, work injury, retirement, unemployment and maternity benefits just like their chinese co-workers. Expats wanting coverage will have to pay a percentage of their wages for the program, while the exact details have yet to be disclosed, most people feel it will be similar to what Chinese workers currently pay, which is about 11% of their total monthly income.\n\nAccording to <a href="http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2011-06/29/content_12797988.htm">China Daily</a> 58 percent of 164 foreign respondents said they were willing to participate in the program, but there are many concerns about the new program including doubts about how well the program will be managed, details about benefits, and the impact of higher cost to employers and foreign companies doing business in China. For those foreigners who plan to stay in China long term, and possibly even after retirement the program is seem as a positive addition. Some workers also feel the program will allow them better access to cheaper more efficient medical services and programs while living and working in China.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nForeign workers in China will soon be covered by the country\'s social security program, according to the Social Insurance Law, which will take effect on Friday.\n\nThe new law will allow foreign employees to receive medical, work injury, retirement, unemployment and maternity benefits similar to those for Chinese citizens.\n\nDetailed regulations are yet to be published. In early June, the Ministry of Human Resources and Social Security solicited public opinion on a set of temporary measures for the program, which stipulates that all registered foreign workers with a valid work permit in China should be covered.\n\nAbout 600,000 foreigners lived on the Chinese mainland at the end of 2010, according to the latest national census. Approximately 231,700 had work permits, the ministry said.\n\nForeign workers employed by Chinese and overseas-funded enterprises, social groups, law firms and foundations that register in China, as well as foreign workers assigned to China by overseas-registered companies, are all subject to the coverage requirement stipulated by the Social Insurance Law.\n\nParticipation in the program means foreign workers\' take-home pay will shrink, because part of their wages will be put into the pension fund, and that their employers\' costs will increase.\n\nWorkers from countries that have signed social insurance agreements with China could be exempted from the program, said Xu Yanjun, deputy director of the ministry\'s social security center. So far, only Germany and the Republic of Korea have signed such agreements.\n\nInternationally, such treaties are aimed to close gaps in social security coverage for people who migrate between countries. For instance, the United States has signed international social insurance agreements with 25 countries.\n\nWhile the details have not been released, experts say the social insurance program for expats will be similar to the one that applies to Chinese citizens.\n\nCurrently, Chinese citizens (depending on the province they live in) pay at least 11 percent of their monthly income to social security - 8 percent to pensions, 2 percent for medical and 1 percent for unemployment. There are both lower and upper limits for the payment. A Chinese citizen pays 1,000 to 1,200 yuan ($154-$185) a month.\n\n<strong>Varied response</strong>\n\nReviews from foreigners are mixed. A recent online survey conducted by China Daily found that nearly 58 percent of the 164 foreign respondents are willing to participate in China\'s social security policy while working here.\n\nClare Pearson, a British national who moved to China five years ago, works at a Chinese magazine in Beijing. She said she welcomes the new initiative of the government.\n\n"I think it\'s a good move, which could benefit foreigners like me who love to stay and work in this country," she said. "I don\'t care about the monthly social insurance fees that I should pay, because such a measure would make me feel that I\'m no longer an outsider but a part of the country."\n\nIsmael, who didn\'t want his full name used, is a 28-year-old Frenchman who has worked for a Chinese company in Beijing for more than three years. He thinks foreign employees who plan to work long-term for a company in China, under contract, will be willing to pay for the insurance because the financial burden will be shared with the employer.\n\nHe is partly covered by expensive private insurance provided by his company. He has been considering applying for coverage in China provided by a French company. "However, it is also extremely expensive in absence of a partnership on the matter between France and China," he said.\n\nCompared with going to a "fancy" hospital with English-speaking staff, he said, treatment in a standard Chinese hospital is cheaper and efficient. "It is unfair that non-citizens would be excluded from mandatory social security coverage," he said.\n\n<strong>Why some say no</strong>\n\nReasons cited by survey participants who rejected the idea included doubt over how the premium will be managed, limited information about the benefits and possession of social security in their home countries.\n\nSome simply didn\'t want income deducted for the premium because they don\'t intend to be in China for long.\n\nMelia, who gave just her first name, is a 30-year-old Indonesian who doubted she would stay long enough to collect her pension and she worried that it will be difficult to claim a refund when she leaves China or changes jobs. She has been assigned to China for 1 years by an Indonesian company, and she works in Xiamen, East China\'s Fujian province.\n\nLu Xuejing, a social security expert at Capital University of Economics and Business, said that the new regulation would be more popular with foreigners who planned to stay in China even after retirement.\n\nTake endowment insurance, for instance. In China, workers pay 8 percent of their wages and employers pay an amount equal to 20 percent of workers\' wages each month to workers\' pension accounts. Workers must contribute for at least 15 years to collect a pension after retiring.\n\nNotably, distrust over the fund management ranked as the top reason, chosen by 30 percent of those who frowned upon the idea, the survey found.\n\nA Filipino working for an education company in Xiamen said insurance companies are the biggest winner of this new social insurance program.\n\n"I think the only people who will see any benefits are those who married Chinese citizens and are planning to reside long term. They are only a small group among all expats living in China," she said, asking not to be named.\n\n"But obviously the insurance companies are definitely benefiting a lot from this program. And we don\'t know who will manage the fund and how."\n\nThe quality of the services she will receive from the program is another concern.\n\n"I don\'t use the company\'s prescribed health insurance, because I don\'t like the public hospitals." She said it is unreasonable to ask her to pay about 10 percent of her salary only to be treated in crowded public hospitals.\n\n<strong>Employer costs</strong>\n\nFor employers, the cost might be the top concern.\n\nSome US companies think the new law may decrease their profits and increase their personnel management costs in China.\n\nShanghai-based law firm Haworth &amp; Lexon estimated that a foreigner holding a work visa in Shanghai will pay up to 1,285 yuan a month to the central government under the law. The employer will need to pay up to 4,323 yuan to the social insurance program.\n\nDavid Dai, senior manager of human resources at the Chinese offices of Jones Lang LaSalle, a global real estate management group, said, "We may change a series of HR policies, like a revision of commercial insurance for foreigners. Salary structure due to tax exemptions (up to 38 percent) may no longer be legal."\n\n"Once the new regulation comes into practice, our cost will increase substantially," said a human resources manager who didn\'t want to be named at a Chinese company employing about 60 foreigners.\n\nFor the health insurance alone, "We have to spend 800,000 yuan more."\n\nTwo business newspapers reported that the European Union Chamber of Commerce in China has urged the Ministry of Human Resources and Social Security to make contributions for foreigners optional.\n\n<strong>Workplace fallout</strong>\n\nSome foreigners worry that the increased costs could result in a deteriorated working environment if employers try to dodge the increased expenses.\n\nA foreign worker at an overseas-funded manufacturing services company in Shanghai, who didn\'t want to be named, said he\'s afraid his employer may want to lower his salary when the new policy takes effect.\n\nHe pays for his own commercial medical insurance in China. "I\'d rather have control over how the money is spent myself."\n\nThe Filipino who works in Xiamen also is concerned. "If the new program increases expenses too much, I\'m afraid that some companies will likely to reduce the number of full-time legal foreign employees, so you may see an increase in a labor black market, employing foreigners illegally."\n\nShe said she and many foreigners come to China to experience the country. "What I do is to travel for a period of time, then work to make some money, and then hit the road again. And of course I won\'t stay in the country for too long, so I don\'t really need the social insurance.\n\n"I think China should be really careful when making the rules and policies for the social insurance program, which should be more focused on its citizens," she said.\n\nYang Yansui, a public policy and management professor at Beijing-based Tsinghua University, said an agreement on social insurance between China and a foreign country is a prerequisite for including expats in China\'s social insurance programs.\n\nThe agreement should include detailed arrangements for the contribution of social insurance and how the benefits will be transferred between two countries, she said. "Without such arrangement, it is unreasonable to force foreigners to join China\'s social insurance program."\n\nBai Liangze at the Chinese Academy of Personnel Science countered that the new social insurance program gives equal treatment to foreigners working in the country and follows international practices.', 'China gives expats Social Security', 0, '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2011-06-30 22:50:20', '2011-07-01 02:50:20', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2468', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
