on intelligence tools and demographic data, today announced the official go-live of <a title="getchee Website" href="http://www.getchee.com" target="_blank">getchee.com</a>.<span> </span>The folks at <em>getchee</em>, who like to call themselves getchens, intend to use their new site to effectively market and support <em>getchee Enterprise</em> and new, up-and-coming tools that will be release later this year.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial;">The light and fresh design of <a href="http://www.getchee.com/" target="_blank">getchee.com</a> was created by the highly creative marketing team, led by Joshua Roberts.<span> </span>“My focus was to keep things clean and friendly.<span> </span>Many company sites in our region keep things strictly business which takes away from the user experience.<span> </span>Our goal was to deliver our message with user in mind.<span> </span>Our design elements were straight-forward like our products.”</span></p>', 'getchee unveils Website to the public...', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'getchee-unveils-website-to-the-public', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:19', '2013-02-20 05:44:19', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=4', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (5, 1, '2008-07-14 04:37:10', '2008-07-14 08:37:10', '<em>GETCHEE </em>INTRODUCES A WEB-BASED ANALYTIC SOLUTION FOR RETAILERS LOOKING TO EXPAND IN EMERGING REGIONS WITHIN CHINA, INDIA &amp; THE MIDDLE EAST.\r\n\r\n<strong>Asia’s first on-demand, web solution that gives access to rich demographic and consumer data in the world’s fastest growing markets.</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>getchee</em>, an Asian-based leader in location intelligence tools and demographic data, today announced the official release of <em>getchee Enterprise</em>. <em>getchee Enterprise</em> is the first Web-based too that allows the user the ability to access rich demographic and consumer behavior data in the world’s fastest growing regions of China, India, The Middles East and S.E. Asia. <em>getchee Enterprise</em> is a customized online tool for retailers who wish to access valuable, on-demand market data for use in network siting.\r\n\r\nHistorically, retailers with networks in Asia have relied primarily on local, on-the ground information to lead their expansion and site selection needs for network growth.  As competition increases and market economics become more complicated, retailers are seeking analytical means to supplement their local knowledge.\r\n\r\n<em>getchee </em>offers the non-technical user, a simple, easy-to-use, DIY solution to retail site selection and planning. "We know how complicated and inaccurate the data sourcing is in this region. We focused our resources and experience to create a simplified tool which allows immediate access to standardized data and demographic analyses. Clients no longer need to rely on an expensive, on-premise software solution that requires significant training," said getchee CEO, Lauri Young.\r\n\r\n<em>getchee Enterprise</em> is an on-demand platform that can be reached from any Web browser running Internet Explorer or Firefox.  Marketing Manager, Joshua Roberts, describes the business model as "high innovation at a reasonable investment to the end-user." End-user access to the tool comes in the form of a monthly, quarterly or yearly subscription. Users are provided a unique user identification and password which allows them easy-access to rich data and reports within their region of choice. Currently, <em>getchee </em>offers data for over 80 cities. The costs for subscription vary based on the degree of customization.\r\n\r\nPlease visit the friendly people at <a title="getchee Website" href="http://www.getchee.com/" target="_blank">www.getchee.com</a> for more information.', 'Introducing a Web-based site selection solution...', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'getchee-introduces-a-web-based-site-so', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:19', '2013-02-20 05:44:19', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=5', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (10, 1, '2008-07-15 00:23:03', '2008-07-15 04:23:03', 'At getchee, we provide emerging market and demographic data in these countries: China, India, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Pakistan, Philippines, Singapore, Taiwan, Thailand, Turkey, and UAE. We\'ve helped many global brand owners invest intelligently in newly emerging markets.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.getchee.com/">read more</a> | <a href="http://digg.com/tech_news/Location_Intelligence_Online">digg story</a>', 'Location Intelligence Online...', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'location-intelligence-online', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:19', '2013-02-20 05:44:19', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=10', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (12, 1, '2008-07-18 04:31:01', '2008-07-18 08:31:01', '[caption id="attachment_14" align="alignright" width="300" caption="I heard getchee is doing cool things with data..."]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/07/gadgetreadingmessage.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-14" title="Inspector Gadget" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/07/gadgetreadingmessage-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nInspector Gadget was definitely one of my favorite animated series as a kid. Mr. Gadget was so prepared for every situation. Truly a living Swiss Army knife. He seemed to have the perfect tools to solve unique problems as they arose. Whether it be his handy go go gadget sneakers, or gadget helicopter, he had things covered.\r\n\r\nGoing up against Dr. Claw, with his handy sidekicks Penny and Brian, Gadget was really the underdog with a couple of tricks up his sleeve. The tricks just happened to be really creative tools he needed to defeat Claw and save the day.\r\n\r\nSince becoming <em>getchee\'s</em> marketing manager, I\'ve gotten really excited about the creative tools we provide our clients to overcome big challenges in emerging markets. Of course they aren\'t as cool as rocket skates, or the famous go go gadget flower, nonetheless they are pretty sweet.\r\n\r\nWe\'re doing some really great things at <em>getchee </em>with standardized emerging market data. We\'ve been working really hard to add some excellent demographic, interest and intensity layers to incredibly fast growing countries in Asia including: China, India, Thailand and The Philippines.\r\n\r\nSo far our clients have seen real growth and advantages using <em>getchee </em>data and tools. I like to think of us as the Inspector Gadgets of GIS. Johnny on the spot with data. The right solution for the right moment.\r\n\r\nStay tuned for more great news from <em>getchee</em>. A lot is going on around here!', 'Go go getchee data...', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'go-go-getchee-data', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:19', '2013-02-20 05:44:19', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=12', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (21, 3, '2008-07-23 03:17:04', '2008-07-23 07:17:04', 'I am looking forward to our Sales Summit in Shanghai this week. This is a first for us, so it should be  a lot of good sharing and learning. A bunch a colleagues are coming from Taipei. The marketing team has put together a lot of excellent content. Topics for the summit range from updates on China and India data to new product functions.\r\n\r\nNot to be a spoiler, but I am very excited to announce that we have just created a new function in <em>getchee</em> that allows end-users to dynamically draw a trade area based on population parameters (e.g. working population, population by age, sex, etc.).  Cool huh??? Big kudos goes out to our killer developer Alvin. Alvin rocks!\r\n\r\nmore later - ly (wearer of many colorful hats)', 'Converging on Shanghai', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'converging-on-shanghai', '', '', '2010-10-04 23:24:30', '2010-10-05 03:24:30', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=21', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (27, 1, '2008-07-24 23:16:41', '2008-07-25 03:16:41', '[caption id="attachment_31" align="alignright" width="336" caption="Starbucks location in Xintiandi, Shanghai"]<img class="size-medium wp-image-31" style="margin: 2px; border: 1px solid black;" title="sh-xintiandimall1" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/07/sh-xintiandimall1.jpg" alt="Starbucks location in Xintiandi, Shanghai" width="336" height="237" />[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>"Beijing allows protests, but you need a permit." </strong><em>- Shanghai Daily</em>\r\n\r\nI can\'t help but chuckle when I read something like this.\r\n\r\nI\'ve been working out of our Shanghai office for 3 days now. We have just finished a 2 day sales summit, which went over quite well. I know I got a lot out of it. I think we can not only improve the quality of service we provide our clients, but simplify the way we do it.\r\n\r\nI spent yesterday walking around the Xin Tian Di (新天地) area. I was quite impressed with just how many foreign brands have been able to work their way into the Shanghai marketplace. I have heard this area is particularly competitive among global brand owners. Stores tend to pop up here one day, then completely disappear the next. There are a few that have been able to survive longer than others, but what makes them different? Is it that they have the right product for the location?\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">There are over 30,000 people that pass through Xin Tian Di daily, and there are over 8,500 bar and restaurant seats in total (according to Shanghai\'s <em>City Weekend</em>). With such a densely populated area, it makes me wonder what makes or breaks a new bar/restaurant. Is customer segmentation enough? or are there just too many overlapping competitors. These are tough questions.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">I have a suspicion that a good location just isn\'t enough. Global retailers will need to learn how to better serve customers. They need to learn how to make their brand stand out in the minds of consumers. How can they glue one solid, outstanding memory of their brand to their patrons? Methods may vary, but one thing is for sure: This they will have to do.</p>', 'Feel free to protest...', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'feel-free-to-protest', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:19', '2013-02-20 05:44:19', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=27', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (41, 1, '2008-08-06 22:21:04', '2008-08-07 02:21:04', '[caption id="attachment_46" align="alignright" width="300" caption="Shanghai Skyline"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/shanghai-photo11.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-46" title="shanghai-photo11" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/shanghai-photo11-300x168.jpg" alt="Shanghai Skyline" width="300" height="168" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\n<span style="x-small;">The new buzzword is authenticity, or real. So it is claimed in the latest meeting from Amcham.</span>\r\n\r\nBut what is real in our world? Socrates once said that being true is subjective and there is no such thing as the objective truth. Perhaps not in the philosophical world, but it does need to be achieved when it comes down to data-mining. It needs to be real and accurate.\r\n\r\nOn a daily basis, we go through tons of information and statistical numbers to find the closest reflection to the truth of a current situation. In developed countries it is peanuts to find this kind of information. It is readily available down to accurate details as up to one block in Ohio.\r\n\r\nIn Asia, however, it is more difficult to retrieve information on cities and regions. What works in the western countries is not always applicable here. China is a big country, and the information is often inconsistent. Different cities use different standards. Most foreign companies are not allowed to work with GPS devices directly on the streets here. To retrieve real data is all the more a challenging.\r\n\r\nAt <em>getchee</em>, we are collecting and standardizing data. This is such that wealth data in ChongQing would have the same values and metrics as the wealth data in Suzhou. This means that we always have to know about the current situation in these cities.\r\n\r\nOne of my favorite blogs to get updated China news is <a title="All Points Blog" href="http://www.allroadsleadtochina.com" target="_blank">www.allroadsleadtochina.com</a>. Is it objective? It may or may not be. But it does give you an indication of the developments in this ever changing country.', 'Remaining True', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'remaining-true', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=41', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (39, 1, '2008-08-06 23:32:38', '2008-08-07 03:32:38', '[caption id="attachment_51" align="alignright" width="300" caption="Taipei Valley"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/taipei101.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-51" title="taipei101" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/taipei101-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nI\'ve lived in Taiwan for nearly 5 years now. Each year seems to get better than the previous, although I am uncertain of how to describe the differences from year to year. Yesterday, while driving up Yang Ming Mountain, I noticed many people stopped at the side of the road, looking down at Taipei. It was just past dusk, and the city lights had already sprung. Curiosity made me ease my scooter to the side of the road.\r\n\r\nThere were fireworks bursting in the distance. The light lit up small portions of the city for seconds at a time. I could see the contrast of taller buildings against the dark backdrop of the surrounding mountains.\r\n\r\nIt\'s easier to see the outline of Taipei and the surrounding counties at night. The lights help create a border at the edge of the city. Taipei sits comfortably in a valley cradled by steep mountains. I wondered what Taipei would have looked like from this location 30 years ago.\r\n\r\nIt amazes me how much Taiwan has changed in the past 30 years. Although I have only lived here for 5, I often imagine what it must have been like here in the 70s, when Taiwan\'s economy really began to boom. I remember as a kid seeing my toys and electronics with a standard "Made in Taiwan" stamped on the back.\r\n\r\nIf I was around back then, where would my place have been? How was it that Taiwan was able to grow so successfully in such a short amount of time?\r\n\r\nI guess these thoughts are more prevelant now considering I work for a company that helps companies invest in emerging markets. Like Taiwan 30 years ago, many countries in Southeast Asia and in China are developing quite quickly. The amazing thing now is that the tools available for successful expansion in these countries is so much better. I am really interested to see what will happen in 10 years.', 'Taipei. Potential in a valley.', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'taipei-potential-in-a-valley', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:41:01', '2013-02-20 05:41:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=39', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (57, 1, '2008-08-12 23:57:37', '2008-08-13 03:57:37', '<address style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW"><a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/user1963_11571768401.gif"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-59" title="user1963_11571768401" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/user1963_11571768401-212x300.gif" alt="" width="212" height="300" /></a></address> <address style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW"><em>"The customer is always right." -Harry Gordon Selfridge, Sr., 1908.</em></address>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW"></p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW"></p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW">我在負責執行專案的過程中，常常收到來自客戶各式各樣的要求與意見，有時候某些意見與原先的專案規模不盡相同，有時候這些要求則是已經超過了原本專案所定義的規模，而此現象發生在顧問服務型態上的專案更是不勝枚舉。雖說服務客戶的準則之一就是「顧客至上」，但仔細想一想，客戶的要求真的永遠是對的嗎？這個疑問常常在我的腦海中浮現。</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW"></p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW">如果仔細回想客戶為什麼提出要求或是修改的聲音，我發現這通常代表了專案當中必定有某些地方與客戶的期望產生了落差。只是，既然服務建議書以及合約都已經簽了，代表客戶認可專案執行的方式與預計產生的成果，怎麼還會有問題？其實這中間能讓客戶產生問題的地方可多了。舉例來說，以顧問服務型態的專案而言，既然名為顧問服務，裡面必定包含許多為客戶量身訂作的解決方案，像是特定的產業資料分析、競爭力暨市場潛力分析、特定客層型態分析等。如果光從名詞寫法上，乍看之下都不太難理解，只要再經過<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">sales</span>對客戶進行專業的說明，絕大多數都能夠獲得客戶的共識。但是，一但進入實質分析階段，小至對於各類分析當中所應採用的原始資料來源，大至分析過程中所建立的研究模型，客戶都有可能突然發現原先自己對此專案所理解的，與客戶自身使用或者是定義的方式還是有所出入，很容易導致客戶質疑分析結果的可靠度、適用性、甚至於可行性，進而提出修正分析方式或者是更換原始資料使用的意見。這代表專案執行成果與客戶期望產生了落差。這類型的客戶要求，不僅增加專案執行的困難度，也大幅提高專案在時間、金錢、資源等方面成本增加以及結案的風險，對公司來說絕對是弊多於利的狀況。這時候，客戶以其期望值為基準針對專案所提出要求的合理於否就不盡然了。</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW"></p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW"><a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/the-customer-is-always-right-quote-unknown-8876.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-60" title="the-customer-is-always-right-quote-unknown-8876" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/the-customer-is-always-right-quote-unknown-8876-289x300.jpg" alt="" width="289" height="300" /></a>其實，要解決上述狀況的方式有許多種，有些人會採取比較強硬的手法，完全照合約規定行事；有些人則會比較堅持「以客為尊」，以滿足客戶的要求為最高指導原則。不過專案管理的準則之一就是要維護所有利害關係人的權益，這其中當然包括了買賣雙方。所以，當收到客戶的要求或者是意見，我倒是認為可以先判斷這些要求是導因於客戶對執行過程中的哪個<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">/</span>些環節認知有誤，是客戶不認同、不了解、不採納我們所提出的方法？還是客戶在一開始在對於專案的各類分析過程暨產出上產生了與原本期待不符的落差？是客戶端全部的關係人都有意見，還是僅其中一部份人有不同看法？等原因釐清了之後，再進一步針對原因加強與客戶端的溝通，並找出雙方都能夠接受的處理方式<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">(</span>尤其是要確定客戶端主要的利害關係人都能夠認可<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">)</span>，這樣子才算得上是個「<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">win-win</span>」的局面。</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW"></p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW">不管是專案執行或者是買賣產品，遇到客戶的要求或意見在所難免。用損失自身的利益，來滿足客戶的期望，或者是客戶的意見<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">(</span>不論合理與否<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">)</span>一律照單全收處理，不見得是能夠與客戶建立長久關係的最佳方法。說穿了，「客戶永遠是對的」這句話，僅不過是為<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><span style="color: #000000;">管理客戶期望</span></span>的這個動作披上了件華麗的外衣罷了。至於如何圓滿地處理客戶的要求，這真是門藝術，就端看各位的智慧啦！而駑鈍如我，仍還在學習這門藝術的路上辛苦地摸索呢！</p>', '客戶永遠是對的!?', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', '%e5%ae%a2%e6%88%b6%e6%b0%b8%e9%81%a0%e6%98%af%e5%b0%8d%e7%9a%84', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=57', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (66, 1, '2008-08-20 03:55:34', '2008-08-20 07:55:34', '<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/consumers.jpg"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-68" title="Consumers on the go." src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/consumers-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a>The media is full of controversial Olympic stories. If it is not about pulverizing world records, it is about the rise of China.\r\n\r\nCompanies all over the world are looking at this waking dragon, watching how its enormous body will unfold and how it will roar. As if the dragon is made of gold, we are rushing to see if there is any fortune to be made.\r\n\r\nIn the last 8 years, companies have been setting up or expanding their business with the thought that any area they can claim is gold.\r\n\r\nHowever there are only so many pieces you can take and the competition is fierce. Consumers are not easily satisfied anymore and have higher expectations. When I walk through Shanghai, I can count three times the number of Haagen-Dazs’ and McDonalds’ than in the whole of my country (Holland). You wonder how many MORE branches they can open? Same goes for fmcg-brands; how can they possibly increase their market share?\r\n\r\nHow can you optimize your search and find the next gold-mine without spending tens of thousands of RMB?\r\n\r\nMcKinsey has published many <a href="http://www.mckinseyquarterly.com/Economic_Studies/Country_Reports/Meeting_the_challenges_of_Chinas_growing_cities_2152_abstract" target="_blank">reports</a> recently about the future of urbanization in China. What will happen from now until 2035? One thing is for sure: more consumption! (<a href="http://www.mckinsey.com/mgi/publications/China_Urban_Billion/video/" target="_blank">video </a>-- for those who don’t have time to read)\r\n\r\nKnow where your consumers are located. Reports like these back up getchee methodology, with a database of over 100 cities detailing demographics and economics. We help you find the gold-mine you are looking for.', 'The China Dream', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-china-dream', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=66', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (89, 1, '2008-08-26 23:07:28', '2008-08-27 03:07:28', '[caption id="attachment_91" align="alignright" width="258" caption="Beijing Olympics -- It was good!"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/beijingolympics.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-91" title="beijingolympics" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/beijingolympics-258x300.jpg" alt="Beijing Olympics -- It was good!" width="258" height="300" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nI have to say that this was one of the best Olympics I have ever seen. Not necessarily because of the quality of performances, or even the fact that it was hosted by one of the fastest growing countries in the world. The thing that made this Olympics different for me was the coverage. For the first time in history, the Internet far outweighed the television.\r\n\r\nThis year, there were about 2,000 hours of Olympic coverage shown on TVs around the world. That\'s a lot by any standard. The amazing thing is that rich media driven Websites delivered well over 4,000 hours to users worldwide.\r\n\r\nIt was an advertisers dream. Millions of viewers tuned in, via their high speed networks, to absorb and digest global branding and advertising campaigns.\r\n\r\nIn the years leading up to the Beijing Olympics, global brand owners rushed to make sure they would be at the scene far before the opening ceremony. There are now a plethora of foreign brands that are left in the wake of the 2008 Beijing Olympics. How will these brands fare now that the bandwagon has come and gone?\r\n\r\nI think we are going to see some very interesting things begin to happen over the next year in China. I\'m not a fortune teller by any means, but I do think that some of these brands may have over-extended themselves. They may have been so concerned with making sure they got into China in time, that they didn\'t put enough thought into their network locations and coverage analysis.\r\n\r\nThis is where we (<em>getchee</em>) have been helping global brands. Since we have gone to great lengths to provide standardized and accurate data on cities in China, we\'ve been able to help big western retailers safely locate sites throughout this emerging market. This is an invaluable service, especially now, as location intelligence in China is nearly impossible to find.', 'Post Olympics. What happens to foreign brands now?', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'post-olympics-what-happens-to-foreign-brands-now', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=89', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (110, 1, '2008-09-11 22:29:08', '2008-09-12 02:29:08', '[caption id="attachment_111" align="alignright" width="208" caption="Can&#39;t we all just get along?"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/gis-vs-local.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-111" title="gis-vs-local" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/gis-vs-local.png" alt="" width="208" height="195" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nMapping, demographics and GIS are valuable tools for finding site locations in unfamiliar cities. They have helped some of the world’s largest global retailers expand efficiently throughout China in several industries including banking, retail and food &amp; beverage.\r\n\r\nGlobal brands have realized the power GIS has to offer. What will it take for local (Chinese) brands to do the same?\r\n\r\nChina is a huge city that rapidly changes and grows daily. No matter where you look in China, you’ll find a diverse cultural and historical context. My clients face real problems when trying to grow in unfamiliar parts of this country. They don’t know how big the market is and they don’t fully understand how to effectively locate their customers. Traditional methods in the past have been to open up one store at a time to test the waters, so to speak. This is pretty risky and takes quite a lot of time to assess whether or not your strategy is working. Also, it provides ample time for competitors to get a jump on you.\r\n\r\nLocal companies tend to feel they know China best. Who am I to disagree? After all, I was born and raised in Shanghai, and I feel I know this city very well. When I engage with local companies, it takes some convincing to show the benefit of complimenting local knowledge with the power of GIS. The last thing we want to do at <em>getchee</em> is tell our local clients that we know better than them. We try to make GIS a very accessible solution to accompany local expertise.\r\n\r\nKnowing where to put new site locations and how to realize market potential in Asia can truly be a difficult thing. This is best done with local knowledge backed by GIS and data from companies like <em>getchee</em>.', 'GIS vs. Local Knowledge', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'gis-vs-local-knowledge', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=110', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (116, 3, '2008-09-12 06:24:21', '2008-09-12 10:24:21', 'I considered writing a lengthy post about the differences between data in Asia vs. data in the West.   Instead, I found some clever images created by a Chinese, who grew up in Germany.   (sorry name unknown)  The <strong><span style="color: #0000ff;">BLUE</span></strong><span style="color: #000080;"> </span>represents a Westerner and the <strong><span style="color: #ff0000;">RED</span> </strong>represents an Easterner.\r\n\r\n- lauri\r\n\r\nP.S. You can find more images at: http://www.mountainrunner.us/2008/01/differences_between_eastern_an.html\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_128" align="alignleft" width="300" caption="&quot;Opinion&quot;"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/opinion2.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-128" title="opinion" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/opinion2-300x156.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="156" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_125" align="alignright" width="300" caption="&quot;Things that are new&quot;"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/things-that-are-new1.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-125" title="things that are new" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/things-that-are-new1-300x156.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="156" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_130" align="alignright" width="300" caption="&quot;Population&quot;"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/population.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-130" title="population" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/population-300x156.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="156" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_123" align="aligncenter" width="300" caption="&quot;At a Party&quot;"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/party.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-123" title="party" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/party-300x156.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="156" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_121" align="alignleft" width="300" caption="&quot;Me&quot;"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/me.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-121" title="me" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/me-300x156.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="156" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_118" align="alignleft" width="300" caption="&quot;Anger&quot;"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/anger.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-118" title="anger" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/anger-300x156.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="156" /></a>[/caption]', 'Data Differences', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'data-differences', '', '', '2010-10-04 23:24:30', '2010-10-05 03:24:30', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=116', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (134, 1, '2008-09-21 23:30:57', '2008-09-22 03:30:57', '[caption id="attachment_135" align="alignright" width="300" caption="A bustling Shanghai night."]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/shanghai-night.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-135" title="shanghai-night" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/shanghai-night-300x226.jpg" alt="A bustling Shanghai night." width="300" height="226" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nNot so long ago, a client asked us to do 40+ tier city study on a 1x1 km grid of China. They wanted it to be complete within 3 months as they planned to roll out their new initiative by winter 2008. The client came from the US and had some successful experiences in South East Asia. Although they saw Shanghai as a very modern city, I wonder if they had the chance to visit some of the tier 2 &amp; 3 cities in which they were planning to expand their business.<br><br>\r\n\r\nMany of the big players in this industry have access to a lot of data that they can purchase at once. This data is collected from numerous vendors, and they all use their own standards for processing and quality control. The data is processed and cleansed until it is ultimately fit for analysis. Often what happens is that it becomes difficult to know the true source from which the data came. It could potentially be corrupt, given the fact that different vendors use different methodology for standardizing and processing location-based data. How do you know that they use the same standards across different regions?<br><br>\r\n\r\nAt <em>getchee</em>, we use one standard for processing location-based data for countries in Asia. We control all processes, starting from the first layer, which is collecting data first hand. I work daily with a dedicated team that continuously processes data with meticulous precision. They are out there on the streets and come back with raw data. We cross check this data and clean it before putting it in our system for further use. Only then we can absolutely guarantee that the output is at least 80% accurate. Data will rarely be 100% accurate. I would be fooling myself and the client to think that we could produce 100% accuracy. There is no such thing, especially in emerging markets such as China. We only need to look at Beijing, where so many stores have popped up like mushrooms just before the Olympics, and how many will remain standing 3 months from now.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThat is why creating data and standardizing it with one process is not easy. The market is changing quickly. Today\'s collected material is tomorrow\'s old news. Different cities and different regions use different systems (e.g. in Beijing we have the famous Hutongs, but in Shanghai they are called Nong). How can we make sure that clients understand this when we present this in <em>getchee Enterprise</em>, our online software? That is one of the challenges we face everyday when we want to apply one systematic methodology to our data and give it the quality it needs to be.<br><br>\r\n\r\nWe know the information that we produce is important for our clients and it needs to be correct and accurate; to this we truly care. When we received this request from our client, we openly talked about the challenges of the quality if this project would have to be finished within 3 months. I know the client preferred a “yes” answer, but they also appreciated our commitment to deliver only the best output possible. In the end, the client didn’t walk away and we found an alternative.', 'Data Quality not Data Quantity', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'quality-is-what-we-deliver', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=134', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (149, 1, '2008-09-23 22:15:46', '2008-09-24 02:15:46', '<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;">這陣子我常接到某位客戶的來電，詢問有關選點方面的看法。最近他們的通路部門正嘗試著使用<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">getchee</span>市場分析工具所提供的各類資料，找出具有高市場潛力的區域，作為考慮設點的標的。可是，由於這跟其內部以往選點的作業及分析方式不同，業務單位對通路部門從<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">getchee</span>上產出的資料有諸多不同的聲音與質疑，讓通路部門的同事很困擾，不知道該用什麼樣的方式與業務單位溝通比較好。所以他來電求援，想聽聽看<em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">getchee</span></em>這邊對於選點的方式有沒有好的建議。</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;">其實這位客戶並不是第一個提出如何在分析上應用<em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">getchee</span></em>資料問題的使用者，許多不是很了解地理環境資料使用的人，大多會有相類似的疑惑。這些問題的背後，牽涉到了幾個層面，一個是企業內部既行的市場分析模式—多以數字為導向為大宗，另一個是企業針對選點所建立的條件假設，還有則是企業內部使用者對於<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><em>getchee</em> </span>這類市場決策分析工具的熟悉度。大多數人在進行選點時，多半先看數字的大小來下初步決定—選居住人口數高的，選辦公大樓多的，或者直接選大眾運輸交會處密集的。當符合條件的地區篩選出來之後，才來「修正」或「討論」選址的條件—有沒有其他的主要竸爭者已經存在了、夠不夠支撐所有的主要業務、該選路口還是沿街面等。表面上這樣的選點過程看似有邏輯，如果仔細想想，就會發現其中遺落了幾個重要的問題：潛在客戶是以上班族還是住家為主？營業時間是僅限白天時段還是全天性質？在不在乎同一區域內主要竸爭者的數量？一家店負責多大距離的營業範圍？設點的考量是小區域性質來看還是以縣市角度出發來看通盤佈局<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">...</span>等等。如果使用者自已對選點這件事沒有清楚的假設條件，光靠數字做判斷的話很容易就迷失在數字所營造出的不真實裏。有些使用者可能還會運用所謂的經驗法則，與數字一起搭配進行分析以降低選點失敗的風險。只是經驗法則故然有其可取之處，一但遇上了全面性的佈點檢討、與主要竸爭者在市埸上硬踫硬、或是決定大規模的策略發展計畫時，則就顯得薄弱許多。這時候如果能使用資料可以在地理環境上立即呈現的分析工具來幫助決策，則就能提供很大的幫助。</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;">當我們協助客戶處理這方面的問題時，除了再三強調選點的假設建立一定要夠清楚之外，其中一項重要的工作，就是教育客戶解讀地理環境的資料。在<em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">getchee</span></em>這套視覺化的市場決策分析工具中，所有各類型的市場資料都是在電子地圖上予以圖像化呈現。不論今天客戶是要進行特定區域內的市場分析，還是要綜覽大環境的發展狀況，使用者都可以在<em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">getchee</span></em>中看到數字落在地理環境上分佈的狀態，很快地就可以判別出那些地方需要優先關心，而那些地方具有開發的市場潛力。尤其<em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">getchee</span></em>提供了多種的資料型態，像是<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">poi</span>市場興趣點、依標凖地理單位計算的統計資料、用不規則型態以及顏色深淺來表現之各類活動聚集強度等，使用者在進行選點或者市場分析時可運用的方式就變得很多元。至於如何在選址分析的過程中應用這麼多種類的資料呢？通常我們會建議使用者採「<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">top-down</span>」的方式來看市場—即從<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">macro market</span>到<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">micro market</span>的概念。首先可使用<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">intensity</span>型態的資料來了解整體大環境的長像，找出有問題或是值得觀注的區域。接著可依分析的目的選用適當的資料種類，來找出符合其假設的小範圍目標區域，例如使用客製化的<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">segment</span>資料、依標凖單位面積或行政界計算的統計數據等，進行進一步的篩選。然後根據選點的假設，對篩選後的區域進行各精細的分析，像是包括竸爭者的數量計算、市場淨值的估計、甚至是設點後的各點優劣排序等，都可以透過<em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">getchee</span></em>得到循序漸進的分析結果。使用者從<em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">getchee</span></em>的操作當中，不僅可即時看到數字反應在地理上的結果，還可獲得系統精算後的各類數字，結合在內部的分析報告中。經過這樣子的程序所產出的選址決定，相信比單就看數字與經驗法則來判斷，要來得可靠多了。</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">gethcee</span></em>這套市場決策分析工具想要帶給使用者的經驗，並不是替換掉使用者原本進行的分析方法，而是希望協助客戶提升現行的分析方式，讓選址與市場分析更為客觀，結果更具可信度，並加速制定決策的過程。<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><em>getchee</em>—</span>結合資料與圖像的視覺化市場決策分析工具，所帶給使用者的，將遠比數字本身多更多呢！</p>', '視覺化市場決策分析工具的力量', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', '%e8%a6%96%e8%a6%ba%e5%8c%96%e5%b8%82%e5%a0%b4%e6%b1%ba%e7%ad%96%e5%88%86%e6%9e%90%e5%b7%a5%e5%85%b7%e7%9a%84%e5%8a%9b%e9%87%8f', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=149', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (154, 1, '2008-09-29 22:25:11', '2008-09-30 02:25:11', '[caption id="attachment_155" align="alignright" width="300" caption="Parents line up to treat infected victims."]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/sanlu1.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-155" title="sanlu1" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/sanlu1-300x244.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="244" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nFlooding the headlines for weeks now has been the China tainted milk powder scandal. It has caused the death of four babies and sickened more than 54,000 children, not to mention causing national and global anxiety.\r\n\r\nThe milk scandal erupted last month when the public learned that melamine, which is used to make plastics and fertilizer, had been found in milk powder and was linked to kidney stones in children and babies. Other milk products, such as liquid milk, yogurt and products made with milk have also been found to be contaminated. The hardest hit areas are found mainly the northern provinces of China. Medical aid and advice needs to be deployed effectively to provide information and support to prospective victims and parents.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_157" align="alignleft" width="209" caption="Tainted Milk Infected Areas"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/sanlu_infant_formula.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-157" title="sanlu_infant_formula" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/sanlu_infant_formula-209x300.jpg" alt="Tainted Milk Infected Areas" width="209" height="300" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nA quick analysis on the population of Tianjin (11 million people), reveals different concentration levels of impacted areas where a high density of 0-5 year olds are found. The sample case shows level-5 areas are high residential areas with many children, therefore more mobile care units are needed.\r\n\r\nThese mobile care units can be the direct contact point for concerned parents and if medical supplies permit, even preliminary health checks can be done. This way, the problem can be rectified quickly.\r\n\r\nLocation intelligence can help reveal which supermarkets or hyper marts sold more tainted milk. This information can be used with mapping to help the re-calls of the contaminated products.\r\n\r\nThe population was projected from 2005 statistics.\r\nMethodology is owned by <a href="http://www.pacific-geopro.com/" target="_blank">GeoPro</a>, with data provided by <a href="http://www.getchee.com/" target="_blank"><em>getchee</em></a>.\r\n\r\nCase study assumptions: baby–toddlers from 0-5 years, residential areas, supermarkets/hyper marts which distributes milk products.', 'Deploy Medical Aid for Poisoned Milk Consumers with Location Intelligence', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'deploy-medical-aid-for-poisoned-milk-consumers-with-location-intelligence', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=154', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (171, 1, '2008-10-27 02:57:16', '2008-10-27 06:57:16', '[caption id="attachment_178" align="alignright" width="300" caption="Points of Interest"]<a href="http://katib.lunarbreeze.com/~getchee0/blog/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/clip_image002.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-178" title="clip_image002" src="http://katib.lunarbreeze.com/~getchee0/blog/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/clip_image002-300x133.jpg" alt="Points of Interest" width="300" height="133" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou have seen them around; they stand at the door openings looking at you. With an instant screening process they can decide if you should be approached or not. When you are in a rush, you walk by them without saying a word, or increase your pace and say you are late for a meeting once they flag you down. I am talking about surveyors!\r\n\r\nI mentioned in a previous post that we have a dedicated team who are out on the streets collecting information through surveys, not only from consumers but also point of interest data. They are verifying that no road was left out of their survey. Did I mention of this all happens without a GPS? Due to laws and regulations, foreign companies are not allowed to own and use GPS devices in China.\r\n\r\nIf only we were able to implement GPS systems, our work would be so much easier! It is not the case, however, and we have to do it the old-fashion way; with a pen, paper-map, a notebook and a good pair of shoes. Our guys are out there rain or shine making sure the maps and related information are correct.\r\n\r\nThese people collect the raw data for necessary to make intelligent business decisions. This data is enough to arm you with the knowledge necessary to know what side of the street to open your coffee store on.\r\n\r\nThey do this day in and day out to make sure we are able to capture what is out there. These guys walk kilometers everyday or stand hours in a shopping area asking questions. Their hard work ultimately helps you make better decisions.\r\n\r\nI think it is a job that people take for granted, and we don’t spend enough time realizing this. Next time when you see them in the field, please do them a favor and make their work enjoyable by answering a few questions.\r\n\r\nNow will all the surveyors please stand up and receive a warm applause?', 'All surveyors please stand up!', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'all-surveyors-please-stand-up', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=171', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (181, 1, '2008-10-27 03:31:56', '2008-10-27 07:31:56', '<strong>Press Release: <em>getchee </em>Expands Automotive Clients</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>getchee</em>, a Taipei-based data and Web analytic company announced collaboration with <a href="http://pacific-geopro.com/" target="_blank">GeoPro</a>, a professional management services company, to expand services to automotive clients.\r\n\r\n“This new target industry marks a continued relationship that GeoPro and <em>getchee </em>have fostered since <em>getchee’s</em> induction in 2007,” said Bruce Berkman, Chairman of <em>getchee</em>. “We look forward to providing great value map data for automotive professionals throughout the region.”\r\n\r\nGeoPro will provide custom management consulting services to automotive clients to expand their brand, and adopt <em>getchee Enterprise</em> to visualize the project data and outputs.\r\n\r\n“While world economies aim to balance in today’s turbulent conditions, managers are compelled to make even more strategic assessments on market planning, ” says Wong Chin Chu, Product Marketing Manager of <em>getchee</em>. “Seeing is believing, and the availability of online data, by <em>getchee</em>, is changing the way retailers seek and make location decisions.”', 'getchee Expands Automotive Clients', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'getchee-expands-automotive-clients', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://katib.lunarbreeze.com/~getchee0/blog/?p=181', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (183, 1, '2008-10-28 23:44:38', '2008-10-29 03:44:38', '<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW"><a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/intensity-sample-1.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-184 alignright" title="intensity-sample-1" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/intensity-sample-1-300x227.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="227" /></a>近年來最嚴重的金融海嘯狠狠地衝擊了世界各國的經濟，在一片哀鴻遍野聲中，仍舊有不少的公司持續著市場開發的腳步，試圖在低迷的不景氣中殺出一絛生路。不過由於零售市場的整體消費力萎縮，該如何重新調整零售點在地理市場上的佈局，使其更能夠發揮最大效益，則成了業者們需處理的首要課題。最近我的客戶就問我：在<em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">getchee</span></em>的市埸決策分析系統中有一種資料叫<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">intensity</span>，這可以怎麼樣應用來幫助我的分析呢？其實，如果想要很快地抓出巨觀市場中該專注的區域，這時候，使用能在地理環境上展現聚集強度的<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">intensity</span>型態資料，對於整體發展網絡的檢視，可就幫了大忙了。</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW">所謂<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">intensity</span>型態的資料，即是將目標資料內的所有數字予以分級<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">(</span>通常分為<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">5</span>級<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">)</span>，運用顏色的漸層<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">(</span>即由淺到深<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">)</span>，來表現數字由小到大的各組距，然後在地圖上呈現其分佈，形狀通常為不規則的形狀。對使用者來說，使用這種型態的資料，可以很快地幫助其在短時間內找出哪些區域是該優先關心的，或者反過來優先刪去最不具有開發價值的地區。<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">intensity</span>型態的展現方式可適用於不同種類的資料，像是目標客群、推估的市場潛力、竸爭對手的數量、以及基本的人口統計資料等。在使用方式上，使用者可以在<em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">getchee</span></em><span style="font-style: normal;">市埸決策分析</span>系統中開啟<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">intensity</span>型態的圖層，搭配分析所需的<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">POI</span>，很容易地就可初步辨示出市場的缺口所在。因為各等級之間有相對性的比較關係，孰高孰低很容易就看得出來。當所有的市場缺口已經被定義出，接下來便可再針對有興趣的目標地區進行進一步的分析與研究。由於這類型的資料很容易閱讀與理解，大大地節省了開發者進行市場判斷與制定決策的時間成本。</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW">不過，客戶也曾問過我，既然實務作業上還是得產出精細的資料來作進一步的市場調整策略的依據，使用<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">intensity</span>型態的資料不是多此一舉嗎？其實不盡然。別忘了，<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">intensity</span>型態資料的最大優點就是快、狠、準─快速反應市場長像、簡潔解讀市場資訊、以及準確找到目標地區。尤其是在分析一個不熟悉的新市場時，與其一開始花時間沒有目的地掃遍各式各類的所有資料，還不如先用<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">intensity</span>資料來抓出該花時間好好研究的區域來得有效率。除非有任何特別的理由非得從一開始就遍覽群文，不然，這麼好用的資料，何不善加利用呢<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">?</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW">這裏也有一個小提醒要告訴大家。由於<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">intensity</span>型態的資料是應用組距的概念將數字分級來表達環境現況，並無法精確告訴使用者某一網格或是某一不規則範圍內實際的數字是多少。不過使用者可以確切地知道，在地理環境上，一定有地區落在<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">intensity</span>資料中各組距的上下限，對判斷市場潛力的落差有很大的幫助。有機會的話，不妨來體驗一下<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">intensity</span>資料與<em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;">getchee</span></em><span>市埸決策分析系統</span>所帶給你的便利喔！</p>', '瞄準目標市埸，抓住發展機會的好幫手 - Intensity Data', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', '%e7%9e%84%e6%ba%96%e7%9b%ae%e6%a8%99%e5%b8%82%e5%9f%b8%ef%bc%8c%e6%8a%93%e4%bd%8f%e7%99%bc%e5%b1%95%e6%a9%9f%e6%9c%83%e7%9a%84%e5%a5%bd%e5%b9%ab%e6%89%8b%e2%94%80intensity-data', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=183', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (189, 1, '2008-11-10 21:41:35', '2008-11-11 01:41:35', '[caption id="attachment_195" align="alignright" width="94" caption="Starbucks Coffee Thailand - A Case Study"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/starbucks-logo.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-195" title="starbucks-logo" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/starbucks-logo.png" alt="Starbucks Coffee Thailand - A Case Study" width="94" height="95" /></a>[/caption]\r\n<h3><strong>Problem</strong></h3>\r\nWith escalating capacity and competition, time and speed to market in untapped territories increase Starbucks’s effort to remain a leader in the Thai marketplace.\r\n<h3><strong>Solution</strong></h3>\r\nA <em>getchee</em> system to segment different demographics and estimate sales potential of a given area, based on customer visits and expenditure per ticket.\r\n<h3><strong>Summary</strong></h3>\r\n<em>Company </em>- Starbucks Coffee Thailand, a wholly owned subsidiary of the Starbucks Corporation, with its first store open in July, 1998, is a relatively young presence in Thailand, nevertheless has seen rapid expansion throughout the nation in the past decade. Of the total 131 stores in Thailand, 94 are located in Bangkok. The core Store Development team, made up of 3 people, has their vision to continue expanding within Bangkok, a market that looks saturated at first glance, but is still believed to have great potential. The strategy is to unearth hidden pockets in the city where a primary target audience of 16-44 year olds can be found in high concentrations. A single store generally serves an average of 200-300 customers a day. Malls with a rounded tenant mix are attractors and popular streets with heavy footfall seem like strong locations. Careful store planning is necessary to justify a minimum investment of 250k USD per store.\r\n\r\n<em>Challenge </em>- Neighborhood demographic data in emerging markets, including Thailand, retain at a macro level and surveys carried out to increase granularity bear high costs. Traditionally, Starbucks Coffee Thailand had deployed information from paper and digital maps, and assembled data with further support from site surveys to make siting decisions. With added local knowledge and gut feeling, short-listed locations are pretty much set for store execution. With escalating capacity and competition, time and speed to market in untapped territories increase Starbucks’s effort to remain a leader in the Thai marketplace.\r\n<h2 style="text-align: center;"><span style="color: #c5da46;"><strong><em>“Instead of augmenting our best practices, getchee gives me a quick glance of an area so I have a good sense of the kind of trade area the potential store is in.”</em></strong></span></h2>\r\nManual labor, a concerted effort, sees a new light as location intelligence with enhanced data and mapping capabilities added a new dimension to the development process. As a regional effort, <em>getchee</em>, Asia’s only location intelligence mapping tool recommended to the local team by the Asia Pacific head office located in Hong Kong, increased efficiency mainly by saving time on data collection and enhancing siting capabilities by validation of target demographics and location dynamics. “Instead of augmenting our best practices, <em>getchee</em> gives me a quick glance of an area so I have a good sense of the kind of trade area the potential store is in”, says Supoj, Development Manager of Starbucks Thailand. Demographics distilled to a trade area size as small as 200m are made available via quick reports, easily printable or shared through <em>getchee’s </em>Enterprise tool.\r\n\r\n<em>Result </em>- Based on Starbucks\' specific target audiences, <em>getchee</em> is able to segment the different demographics of the population and estimate the sales potential for a given area based on customer visit frequency and expenditure per ticket.\r\n<h2 style="text-align: center;"><span style="color: #c5da46;"><strong><em>“We can’t cut and paste U.S. standards of siting in these regions, but with getchee, a pattern can begin to form.”</em></strong></span></h2>\r\nFurthermore, enriched proprietary data such as day-time and working population gives the team an even more accurate estimation of transactions during the day compared to night-time. Starbucks Thailand gained answers through hard numbers found conveniently via a few clicks on <em>getchee</em> through the Web. Other advantages the team found were the heat maps which they deemed unprecedented in the market. The maps are customized to the relevance of the coffee business and help visually focus on areas that matter. "These intensity or heat maps save me a lot of time when I\'m making a search", Supoj says. Even in the early stages Starbucks Thailand found <em>getchee</em> uncomplicated to use. With the suggestions and tweaks the team freely shares in the process not only reflect on the output, but improves future product enhancements. Overall, the Asia Pacific head office says that the benefits <em>getchee</em> brings are beyond data and numbers. It is in a standardized process they inculcate through the use of <em>getchee</em> that the regional managers can increase expansion and siting methods in the long term via the same platform. "We can\'t cut and paste U.S. standards of siting in these regions, but with <em>getchee</em>, a pattern can begin to form," Supoj explains.\r\n\r\n<a title="Starbucks Case Study" href="http://www.getchee.com/clients/case-study-files/starbucks-thailand-case-study.pdf" target="_blank">Download this case study.</a>', 'Case Study: Starbucks Coffee Thailand', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'case-study-starbucks-coffee-thailand', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=189', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
