ram name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><param name="src" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/sNTrahOOia0&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1" /><embed type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="425" height="344" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/sNTrahOOia0&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true"></embed></object>\r\n\r\n<strong>Trade Area Analysis</strong> - Understand how your trade areas interact with other trade areas.\r\n\r\n<object classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" width="425" height="344" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0"><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><param name="src" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/7t9Uho0jYac&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1" /><embed type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="425" height="344" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/7t9Uho0jYac&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true"></embed></object>', 'getchee Enterprise - Video Tutorials', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'getchee-enterprise-video-tutorials', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=207', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (218, 1, '2008-11-25 20:36:09', '2008-11-26 00:36:09', '[caption id="attachment_221" align="alignright" width="114" caption="Mickey Mouse"]<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/11/images.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-221" title="Disneyland" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/11/images.jpg" alt="Mickey Mouse" width="114" height="123" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nUsually I write each month about my daily work in beating the great Asian challenge with regards to location and data intelligence. This time it is different; last month I was visiting Disneyland Hong Kong and I truly enjoyed the whole experience.\r\nI believe the Walt Disney Company is one of the most successful marketing stories since the 50’s.\r\n\r\nMy friends all warned me that it was too small, no thrill-rides, not adventurous. They warned me it is for small children; however that didn’t stop us from having a fantastic day, all thanks to the great marketing strategy from the Walt Disney Company!\r\n\r\nAs soon we were in the Disney train that took us to the theme-park, it already set the tone of the whole experience. The magic began at the entrance. We could hear the familiar Disney tunes and feel the energy. We felt like little kids that we once were.\r\n\r\nThe goal of Disneyland is to give you an un-forgettable experience, no matter if you are young or old. The whole idea behind Disneyland is that as a family, young and old can enjoy all activities. Every crew member, (instead of calling them employees; Disney uses the word crew) is fully engaged in their role to make your experience as unforgettable as possible. The total lay-out of the park is not a coincidence, it takes careful planning and decisions into consideration. The way how they display their products is thoughtfully carved out, playing very well into human emotions.\r\n\r\nWhen marketing can hit your soft spot and your emotions, then I believe that it has been successful. The next step is of course to stay aligned with your customer emotions, but that is a whole different story.\r\nFor now I am that little kid who had just experienced being young again when I saw all my favorite Disney figures come back to life and can really play all the adventures that I once saw on TV.\r\n\r\nLast month they decorated the park with a Halloween theme. And being the scary cat that I am, I had the courage to enter one of the ghost-houses and one thing I can say for sure is: Who needs a roller-coaster ride that goes mach 3, when the ghost-house almost made me wet my pants? That is just priceless.', 'Enter the world of Yesterday, Tomorrow and Fantasy', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'enter-the-world-of-yesterday-tomorrow-and-fantasy', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=218', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (242, 1, '2008-12-03 03:16:09', '2008-12-03 07:16:09', '<p><a href="../wp-content/uploads/2008/12/sms4.jpg" mce_href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/12/sms4.jpg"><img src="../wp-content/uploads/2008/12/sms4-275x300.jpg" mce_src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/12/sms4-275x300.jpg" alt="" title="sms4" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-241" width="275" height="300"></a>最近我看到一篇有趣的文章，是關於某日本著名行動業者在<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">Location Commerce(L-Commerce</font>，定位商務<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">)</font>上的應用介紹。以前針對行動通訊服務的應用討論比較廣泛的，大多集中在通訊產品本身的功能以及通訊網絡的建置。自<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">3G</font>服務上路之後，如何發展更多元的服務以及提升使用者的使用意願，成了一大重點，其中又以<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">L-Commerce</font>的發展受到亞洲國家的注意。其實支撐起<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">L-Commerce</font>的概念背後，就是「<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">Location</font>」這個關鍵字，而這也跟<i><font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">getchee</font></i>一直以來在傳達的地理環境空間分析觀念息息相關。\r\n</p><p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" mce_style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW">怎麼說呢<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">?</font>首先從<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">L-Commerce</font>的定義來看起。根據<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">Wikipedia</font>的記載，所謂的<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">L-Commerce</font>，是指利用科技<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">(</font>例如<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">GPS)</font>提供地點資訊用於商業層面的應用<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">(</font>註一<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">)</font>，或者是結合無線網路提供該地區或是該處商家的資訊<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">(</font>註二<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">)</font>。與電子商務最大的不一樣，是<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">L-Commerce</font>有強烈的地點<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">/</font>地域特性，並與在該處活動的人有著密切的相關。對企業來說，以往在實體通路的行銷只能夠針對有「踏進」商店的客群進行，要不就是依賴各類型媒體進行大規模的宣傳，嘗試吸引潛在客群移動到特定通路進行消費。<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">L-Commerce</font>則是把地點跟消費者「綁」在一起～即當消費者移動到哪裏，該處的商店就會主動「告訴」消費者其所在的地方正提供著什麼樣特別的服務，藉以提升潛在消費者購買的意願。</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" mce_style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW">如果單就市場空間的角度來看，<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">L-Commerce</font>的概念對於銷售者在市場佈局上可能會產生以下的影響：<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">1.</font>重新檢討各通路在家數與地理市場的涵蓋度；<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">2.</font>針對不同性質的地理市場，定義更能符合該環境的行銷手法<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">(</font>例如：西門町與信義商圈因客層不同，可進行不一樣的活動通知<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">)</font>；<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">3.</font>更加強化商品與地理環境的結合，或者是反證實際銷售與地理環境的關連性<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">(</font>例如居住密度高的地區是不是真的以居家用品賣得最好，或是複合性商圈真以流行性用品為主打<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">)</font>。這種從地理環境的角度出發來找出行動通訊服務可加值的應用概念，如果能配合<i><font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">getchee</font></i>完整的市場資料，針對區域<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">(</font>而非單一業種或店點<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">)</font>進行進階的市場屬性分析，對於找到「對」的消費者或是補強竸爭力較弱的市場，都有效果加乘的效果。</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" mce_style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW">在<i><font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">getchee</font></i>的市場決策分析工具中，透過一般人所熟知的電子地圖、市場資料<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">(</font>如<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">POI</font>－市場興趣點、<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">intensity</font>密集度資料<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">)</font>、人口統計資料等的資訊展現，能夠幫助使用者很快地辨識出各個微型市場的個性與特徵，作為通路判斷與產品可能適用的行為進行初步的分析。為了幫助使用者更快地找出該鎖定的區域，<i><font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">getchee</font></i>的<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">population query</font>進階分析功能，可以讓使用者自己定義欲鎖定的目標客群種類與數量，經過<i><font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">getchee</font></i>系統運算後，將符合條件的結果標示在電子地圖上。搭配適當種類的<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">POI</font>呈現，以視覺化的資訊處理，讓使用者很容易就清楚知道哪裏才是<span>發揮戰鬥力</span>「重點區域」。一但戰場明確，在決策與行動上也就能比竸爭者更快一步了。</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" mce_style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW">科技的日新月異，幫助了銷售者拉近與消費者之間的距離，<font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">L-Commerce</font>與<i><font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">getchee</font></i>市場決策分析工具都是其中結合了地理空間環境的概念所發展出的新應用範例。身處在這詭譎多變的市場中，能夠聰明應用新工具並正確發揮其效能的一方，相信絕對更能夠抓得住消費者喔！</p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" mce_style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="zh-TW">\r\n</p><p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" mce_style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"><a class="mceItemAnchor" name="siteSub"></a><span lang="zh-TW">註一：</span><font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">Wikipedia, “L-commerce, ”&lt;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L-commerce" mce_href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L-commerce">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L-commerce</a>&gt;</font></p>\r\n<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" mce_style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"><span lang="zh-TW">註二：楊青，「從香港經驗預測</span><font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">L-Commerce</font><span lang="zh-TW">未來在亞洲將舉足輕重！」，</span><font style="" face="Times New Roman,serif">&lt;<a href="http://209.85.173.132/search?q=cache:ngIH1nfU2FIJ:www.ectimes.org.tw/shownews.aspx%3Fid%3D5473+L-commerce&amp;hl=zh-TW&amp;ct=clnk&amp;cd=9&amp;gl=tw&amp;client=firefox-a" mce_href="http://209.85.173.132/search?q=cache:ngIH1nfU2FIJ:www.ectimes.org.tw/shownews.aspx%3Fid%3D5473+L-commerce&amp;hl=zh-TW&amp;ct=clnk&amp;cd=9&amp;gl=tw&amp;client=firefox-a">http://209.85.173.132/search?q=cache:ngIH1nfU2FIJ:www.ectimes.org.tw/shownews.aspx%3Fid%3D5473+L-commerce&amp;hl=zh-TW&amp;ct=clnk&amp;cd=9&amp;gl=tw&amp;client=firefox-a</a>&gt; (2 Jan. 2004)</font></p>', '萬變不離LOCATION', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', '%e8%90%ac%e8%ae%8a%e4%b8%8d%e9%9b%a2location', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=242', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (246, 1, '2009-01-30 17:18:49', '2009-01-30 21:18:49', '<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"><strong>A quick review of the 3 top mistakes retailers will make when entering China.</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_250" align="alignright" width="300" caption="Shanghai, China"]<img class="size-medium wp-image-250" title="Shanghai" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/01/shanghai-300x150.jpg" alt="shanghai" width="300" height="150" />[/caption]\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"> </span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"><strong>1) What you see is not always what you get.</strong></span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"> </span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US">Imagine a shopping center in Shanghai on an average Friday. There are families with children, young people and those going to work or out to lunch. Immediately you may think this would be an ideal location for your store. You see your target group and the tenant mix in the shopping area is what you want to attract. Your feeling says this is the place, but is that enough to make a decision? – No.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"> </span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US">Chinese people are notorious for browsing and window shopping. They take time to compare products in different stores to ensure the best price. They may also just spend their time in malls because they are nice and warm, especially during the cold winter months.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"> </span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US">When opening a new location, it shouldn’t come down to a gut feeling. It should be based on facts and figures. Your team needs to do their homework, and must be able to back up findings with some sort of scientific process. Opening a new outlet based on a gut feeling can be a huge mistake, considering the fact that you are dealing with a foreign market place, where cultural and social differences can make a significant impact on your bottom line.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"> </span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"><strong>2) Understand the culture.</strong></span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"> </span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US">You need to know the local culture and traditions of the region you want to enter. The last thing you want to do is open a store that only collects dust.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"> </span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US">Shanghai as a mega-city, looks very modern and open, but when you scratch the surface you see a whole different layer, where old customs and beliefs are still in place. People tend to stick to certain brands because of word of mouth or because they are familiar with the product. Knowing this information is vital, because it can help you find out why your competitors outperform you.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"> </span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"><strong>3) Not everybody likes your product. Be innovative!</strong></span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"> </span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US">One of the reasons that KFC is widely popular in China is not because of the fact that the people here are fonder of chicken than beef. (Ok, a little bit is true)</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US">But KFC constantly expands and innovates itself over and over again. It now sells the traditional congee and you-tiao (a long piece of dough deep fried in oil) breakfast. Who would have thought that KFC would sell traditional local breakfast instead next to their famous burgers? If you would have told me this 4 years ago, I would have burst out in laughing and thought it was a good joke.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US"> </span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-US">Accurate and reliable data is hard to come by. Even if you manage to find some, it is not always up-to-date or consistent. What needs to be done is standardize all levels of information so that objective results can be found. Only then can you make an informed and positively healthy decision.</span></p>', '3 Startup Business Mistakes in China', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'top-3-mistakes-when-entering-a-business-in-china', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=246', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (261, 1, '2009-04-12 23:40:23', '2009-04-13 03:40:23', '<img class="alignright size-full wp-image-266" title="data-accuracy" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/data-accuracy.png" alt="data-accuracy" width="300" height="227" />I was reading a small post on the <a href="http://apb.directionsmag.com/archives/P2.html" target="_blank">All Points Blog</a>: The LAPD made an error in their geo-coding and plotted the area around city hall with a high crime rate. This information is totally incorrect.\r\n\r\nIf a geo-coding error can occur like this in the States, where a rich and fresh supply of data is easily accessible, imagine what can happen in emerging economies where such data luxuries are hard to come by. Think of the impact such inaccuracies could have.\r\n\r\nYes we have Google Maps, Microsoft Earth and other mapping engines, but how much faith can we really put in the accuracy of their data?\r\n\r\n“Most spatial data is inaccurate," says Paul Zandbergen, a professor of geography at the University of New Mexico who studies the quality of online maps.\r\n\r\nI think it is important to realize that spatial data is inaccurate, but also it is important to realize that a certain percentage of inaccuracies are acceptable. Of course we can strive to be as accurate as possible, but all the while knowing that 100% accuracy is not within reasonable grasp.\r\n\r\nIn many Asian countries we find data that is dead wrong and or non-existing, and to bring it to an acceptable level of accuracy is as challenging as eating ice cream in Death Valley before it evaporates.\r\n\r\nIt’s a real challenge to convey data discrepancies with clients, but it is crucially important that they know that data cannot possibly be 100 percent accurate. If it isn’t perfect in Western developed countries, where location based intelligence has been around for a long time, how can it be expected that it could be perfect in Asia?\r\n\r\nBut on a positive note, getchee can produce data with a 70 to 80 percent accuracy rate, and that’s something to stay optimistic about.', 'Most spatial data is inaccurate', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'most-spatial-data-is-inaccurate', '', '', '2013-02-20 01:44:01', '2013-02-20 05:44:01', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=261', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (268, 1, '2009-07-31 01:41:41', '2009-07-31 05:41:41', 'This is a great version update that has some great new functionality including:\r\n\r\n<a title="Site Profiler" href="http://www.getchee.com/products/products-index.html#siteProfiler" target="_blank">Site Profiler</a> - You may have a certain store in your network that outperforms others. Wouldn\'t it be nice to profile that store to find other potential top performing sites? getchee Enterprise\'s new site profiler will help you do just that by taking a snapshot of your target store\'s demographic and POI footprint.\r\n\r\n<a title="Point of Interest Settings" href="http://www.getchee.com/products/products-index.html#poiSettings" target="_blank">POI Settings</a> - Easily adjust points of interest per project to help you quickly locate only the POI that you\'re interested in. This will help you weed out the POI that don\'t matter to your business model, saving you valuable time in the end.\r\n\r\n<a title="Estimated Market Potential" href="http://www.getchee.com/products/products-index.html#estimatedMarketPotential" target="_blank">Estimated Market Potential</a> - Quickly locate 1km square grids containing your target customer. Enter dollar values for potential and share to learn your estimated market potential and market share in a particular grid location on the map.', 'getchee Enterprise v1.4 - What\'s new?', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'getchee-enterprise-v1-4-whats-new', '', '', '2013-02-20 03:27:44', '2013-02-20 07:27:44', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=268', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (276, 9, '2009-09-04 04:58:45', '2009-09-04 08:58:45', '<p style="text-align: left;">Forget about the <a title="U.S. Court Bars Microsoft Word Sales - Reuters" href="http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE57B38M20090812" target="_blank">Microsoft court order</a> to pay more than US$290 million in damages for a potential Microsoft Word patent infringement. That number pales in comparison to the numbers that large global retail businesses have been crunching in Excel during this time of economic distress. Yes, the times have been pretty tough. But when the going gets tough, the tough get going. The good news is that the global economy is beginning to pull out of a recession. If you are any part of that tough crowd, you’ve definitely been racking your brain about how and where to expand to increase revenue.</p>\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-280" title="Estimate Market Potential" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/estimate-market-potential.png" alt="Estimate market potential for markets in China, India, and the Middle East." width="539" height="360" />\r\n\r\nWith respect to analyzing a trade area, you know which demographic data weighs heavy when determining your target customer. Advanced economies are posting negative numbers while emerging markets like China and India show growth projections of 5 percent in 2009 and 7 percent in 2010 urge you to grab a piece of the action. Now you’re asking yourself, “Where do I get the most accurate geographic and demographic data so that I can run proper trade area analyses on cities that I’m not extremely familiar with to determine market potential and figure out if an investment is profitable.” Relax, <a title="getchee - business solutions for emerging markets" href="http://www.getchee.com/?utm_source=getchee&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=sept%2B4%2Bblogpost" target="_blank">we\'re</a> experts in Asia.\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Boost revenue by locating your target customer and estimating market potential based on specific demographics.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nOur demographic data, mapping software, and consulting services give you the confidence to make profitable business decisions through precise data at a street level. Even with an emerging behemoth like China, a feature like getchee Enterprise’s estimated market potential breaks down target cities into smaller bite-size pieces. Based on numbers you set for specific demographics like total female population, your estimated market potential (e.g., how much each female will spend per month on a particular product), and the estimated market share you are looking to achieve, you zone in on areas containing your target customer in a matter of seconds.\r\n\r\n<a title="Experience the convenience and cost savings from getchee Enterprise, Asia’s leading location-based Web solution." href="http://demo.getchee.com/mapguide/getchee-demo/register.aspx?utm_source=getchee&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=sept%2B4%2Bblogpost" target="_blank">Locate a gold mine now with <em>getchee</em> Enterprise.</a>', 'Locate Target Customers in China, India, and Other Emerging Markets', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'estimate-market-potential-for-china-india-and-the-middle-east', '', '', '2013-02-20 03:27:44', '2013-02-20 07:27:44', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=276', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (397, 9, '2009-09-18 04:11:10', '2009-09-18 08:11:10', 'Although the current U.S. economic situation is quite bleak, we can look to the Far East for economic relief as <a title="China economy to grow 8 pct in 2010: PBOC\'s Fan" href="http://www.reuters.com/article/ousiv/idUSTRE57N1GG20090824" target="_blank">China’s economy</a> is expected to grow 8 percent in 2010. This doesn’t mean everything is peachy in China. Staying on the positive path, the fast-food industry in China is expected to see a compounded annual growth rate of 25 percent in the coming years, according to RNCOS’s China Fast Food Analysis report.\r\n\r\nBig U.S. fast-food players like Burger King, who’s been hit hard because so many of its restaurants are concentrated in the States, are banking on China to help boost revenue. Burger King’s goal is to open 250 to 300 restaurants across China by 2015. Meanwhile, the Colonel (KFC) has been working on opening at least 300 stores this year.  But don’t let the Western fast-food giants fool you as the Chinese counterparts still occupy nearly 80% of the market share. Grabbing a piece of the pie requires understanding the customer. In order to draw Chinese customers, Burger King is looking to maintain its standards of quality, while adding to its menu local flavors such as Asian sauces, egg burgers, wraps, wings, and salad cups said Jonathan Shih, general manager of Burger King China, in an <a title="Fast-Food Restaurant Comes East" href="http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/bw/2009-08/31/content_8634359.htm" target="_blank">article</a> by China Daily.\r\n\r\n<img title="accurate-data" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/accurate-data.png" alt="accurate-data" width="539" height="106" />\r\n\r\nIf you build it, they will come. The tricky part is figuring out where to build. As the urbanization of China speeds up, large quantities of rural populations flow into the cities, intensifying consumption power. Thus, geographic data showing daytime populations shed light on where and how people commute. Overlaying this information with demographic data like female, male, and working populations help locate specific trade areas containing target customers. Understanding the customer’s preferences in combination with analyzing present-day data on China will be critical to the success of fast-food businesses.', 'Food Fight in China', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'food-fight-in-china', '', '', '2013-02-20 03:27:44', '2013-02-20 07:27:44', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=397', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (350, 9, '2009-09-27 23:23:15', '2009-09-28 03:23:15', 'Expansion and optimization in China are what it’s all about for automotive, retail, and banking industries, but there’s a lot of baggage that comes along with that. How do you grow effectively in area with 22 provinces and over 1.3 billion people? There’s no doubt that the customer is king, so you definitely need local knowledge. Selling nice fluffy pancakes at 8 a.m. isn’t going to cut it when you know everyone wants youtiao, a deep-fried dough stick. Learn firsthand from <a title="KFC Offers Chinese Youtiao" href="http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2008-01/21/content_6409098.htm" target="_blank">KFC</a>. However, knowing what local people like is only half the battle. The other half of the battle is the knowledge gained through objective demographic and market data. The problem is that accurate data for an emerging market like China is scarcer compared to the States, where you can easily obtain great data from companies like <a title="CLARITAS Target Marketing Solutions - Targeting profitable customers and locations every time" href="http://www.claritas.com/Default.jsp" target="_blank">ACNielsen</a>, <a title="ESRI - GIS software that gives you the geographic advantage" href="http://www.esri.com/" target="_blank">ESRI</a>, and <a title="Pitney Bowes Business Insight - Locate, connect and communicate more efficiently" href="http://www.pbinsight.com/" target="_blank">Pitney Bowes</a>.\r\n\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-357" title="knowledge-plus-data" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/knowledge-plus-data.png" alt="knowledge-plus-data" width="539" height="130" />\r\n\r\nYou might as well throw Tylenol into the mix of buzzwords with all those headaches banks have trying to figure out what branch format is needed to cover their target segment. Not to fret though, there’s a light at the end of this data deficient tunnel. There are some <a title="getchee provides demographic data and GIS software solutions to global retail brands for markets in China, India, and The Middle East." href="http://www.getchee.com/" target="_blank">GIS and data solutions</a> available for emerging markets, providing access to fairly granular data including demographic &amp; income profiles, daytime population drivers, and retail/commercial activity. Banking, retail and automotive brands that capitalize on this data will be able to grow efficiently and safely in Asia. They will be able to format and optimize stores/branch locations. Knowing how to make better siting and expansion decisions will put them miles ahead of the pack.\r\n\r\nThere’s a good chance you’re reading this at work. At the same time, you’re thinking about where to eat and what to buy after you leave the office. Funny thing is retailers are doing the same thing. Now what about 1.3 billion Chinese people? It’s time to take a look at those reports again. Rather than analyzing pockets of affluence, focusing on areas that become densely populated during the day helps retailers decide where to place sites and what to sell.\r\n\r\nNumbers, numbers, numbers. They’re everywhere. Objective demographic and market data is needed to make educated business decisions. Standardized data can be used to help systematically organize the way global brands expand and optimize. It’s really all about process.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-391" title="market-report-data" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/market-report-data.png" alt="market-report-data" width="539" height="406" /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\r\n\r\n<strong>What data is available for emerging markets in China, India, and the Middle East?</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Points of interests like coffee shops, department stores, office building, and hotels</li>\r\n	<li>Intensity maps marking business, lifestyle, accessibility, and residential densities</li>\r\n	<li> Population breakdowns by age, gender, and household counts</li>\r\n	<li> Base maps highlighting highways, parks, streets and geographical features</li>\r\n	<li> Customized &amp; value-added datasets consisting of affluent and daytime populations</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a title="Rich data for emerging markets." href="http://www.getchee.com/products/products-data.html" target="_blank">Learn more about data available in emerging markets.</a>\r\n\r\nSuccessful global brands such as Starbucks, McDonald’s, Subway, KFC, HSBC, Standard Chartered Bank, Ford, and GM have relied on standardized market data to efficiently and safely expand in Asia.\r\n\r\n<a title="Who is using getchee?" href="http://www.getchee.com/clients/clients-index.html" target="_blank">More information and case studies available here.</a>', 'Better Business Decisions Using Local Knowledge and Objective Data', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'better-business-decisions-using-local-knowledge-and-objective-data', '', '', '2013-02-20 03:27:44', '2013-02-20 07:27:44', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=350', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (412, 9, '2009-09-29 00:00:33', '2009-09-29 04:00:33', '歡迎光臨 (Welcome)! Accompanied by a slight bow,  歡迎光臨 was the only distinct phrase I could pick out from the surrounding chatter hodgepodge as I hobbled along the moving walkway with a 10-pound schoolbag strapped to my back and bulging black duffel bag dangling from my left crutch. Staring at the 10-digit number I had in my hand, a thunderous thump broke my concentration as the immigration officer stared at me with a wooden stamper in his hand and said, “Welcome to Taiwan!” A chance to blend in with a local, I immediately responded with a jovial 謝謝 (thank  you) and asked the blue uniform clad man where the nearest pay phone was. He pointed, and off I was to the bustling city of Taipei.\r\n\r\nA few weeks into my new life and able to ride the subway without a stranger offering me the priority seat, I was prepared to explore everything Taipei had to offer. Countless hours of sipping on bubble tea and slithering through jam-packed night markets like<a title="Night Markets in Taiwan" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Night_markets_in_Taiwan" target="_blank"> Snake Alley</a> had passed, and there wasn’t a day when I didn’t come across one of Taiwan’s ubiquitous convenience stores or hear talk of the flourishing <a title="Xinyi District - Home of Taipei 101" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xinyi_District" target="_blank">Xinyi District</a>, home of the newly erected Taipei 101.\r\n\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-413" title="fierce-competition-in-Asia" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/here-today-gone-tomorrow.png" alt="fierce-competition-in-Asia" width="539" height="130" />\r\n\r\nFour years later and numerous trips to mainland China under the belt, I found myself residing on the outskirts of the retail saturated area of Xinyi. Even after almost two years of living in Xinyi and six in Taipei, a new convenience store or bank never fails to show its face to me daily. Ironically, the amount of sites with ‘retail space for rent’ signs up hasn’t diminished. Even the Taiwanese equivalent of the Dollar Tree on the first floor of my apartment building slapped me in the face with a black sharpie-marked, 10-digit numbered red piece of paper on my way home from work.\r\n\r\nLabor Day had come and gone and still no indication of a new store. “What would I put there?” I asked myself. Before I could come up with a reasonable answer, a large 50NT sign had replaced the red piece of paper. I came home the next day to a corner full of scooters, a line wrapped around the block, and the smell of oily box meals (<a title="Japanese Bento Boxes" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bento" target="_blank">bento</a> boxes). Scrambling to win its customers back, the shop across the street remodeled and opened up the next day with a 50NT sign above its doors. The shop would probably have a few customers in it if they had opened up the block’s fourth Japanese place rather than compete with 39NT. This vicious market share melee is so commonplace in Taiwan and China that it makes you wonder if there’s a serious lack of trade area analysis or if there really is only one boss in each neighborhood.', 'Bento Battle', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'bento-battle', '', '', '2013-02-25 04:46:58', '2013-02-25 08:46:58', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=412', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
