INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2123, 9, '2011-02-22 03:56:09', '2011-02-22 07:56:09', '<div>\r\n\r\nAlthough  the opportunities for retail success in China are grand, the underlying  challenges are just as daunting. Many firms are finding there is no  substitute to a fact-based, analytical approach to planning store  network development and optimizing business operations across this vast  market. <em>getchee</em> provides a range of support tools and consulting services to increase retail sales productivity and reduce risk.\r\n\r\n<strong>Seminar Details</strong>\r\n<em>getchee</em> will present info on the following points at the third installment of its ongoing seminars.<em>\r\n</em>+ City ranking and market sizing\r\n+ Trade zone selection\r\n+ Cannibalization risk management\r\n+ Competitor overlap assessments\r\n+ Store development process improvements\r\n+ Store performance management improvements\r\n+ Channel &amp; format-mix strategies\r\n\r\n<strong>Date:</strong> April 13, 2011 (Wednesday)<strong>\r\nTime:</strong> 09:00 - 12:00        <strong>\r\nVenue:</strong> Accenture<strong>\r\nAddress:</strong> 31F Zhao Feng Plaza, 1027  Changning Road, Shanghai, China (<a style="color: #9cbd42; font-size: 12px; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; text-decoration: none;" href="http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&amp;source=s_q&amp;hl=en&amp;geocode=&amp;q=1027+Changning+Road,+Shanghai,+China&amp;sll=25.052337,121.550267&amp;sspn=0.010691,0.017574&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;hq=&amp;hnear=China+Shanghai+Changning+Changning+Rd+1027%E5%8F%B7&amp;ll=31.218314,121.418114&amp;spn=0.001262,0.00" target="_blank">map</a>)<strong>\r\nRegistration Fee:</strong> None<strong>\r\nLanguage:</strong> English\r\nFeel free to forward this invitation to interested third parties.<a style="color: #9cbd42; font-size: 32px; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; text-decoration: none;" href="http://events.getchee.com/index.html" target="_blank">\r\n\r\nRegister Now!</a>\r\n\r\n</div>', 'getchee Seminar - Tools & Processes for Store Network Development Success', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'getchee-seminar-tools-processes-for-store-network-development-success', '', '', '2013-02-25 04:41:12', '2013-02-25 08:41:12', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2123', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2154, 9, '2011-03-09 04:27:36', '2011-03-09 08:27:36', '<h1>9am-950am\r\nTopic: APAC – The World’s Economic Powerhouse</h1><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Eric Fishwick, Chief Economist, CLSA</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Asia is still booming and will continue to boom.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Focus markets are China, India, and Japan.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<h1>950am-11am\r\nTopic: Learning &amp; Observing from APAC’s Leading Retailers</h1><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Jerry Black, Chief Strategy Officer, AEON; CEO, Asean; CIO and CEO, Digital Business</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Boost HR and localization.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ How do you utilize scale?</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">1. First figure out your competitive advantages locally then expand abroad.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Customers that shop via 2 channels are 3.5 times more powerful consumers than that of a customer who shops via only 1 channel.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Customers that shop via 3 channels are 5 times more powerful consumers than that of a customer who shops via only 1 channel.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Connect channels, specifically social networks, rather than try to control the customer</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ In the past, margin is what you determine. Now, margin is what you keep not demand because the consumer is in total control.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Engage customers through all social media channels.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Respond to customers via social medial channels rather than focus on mass marketing.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ AEON is looking to empower stores and managers with knowledge about customers to make them happy immediately.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ The key to making customers happy is not focused on being attentive but rather your reactions and time it takes to react.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ As the online retail market grows, he predicts physical stores will shrink in size and the key is to focus on product assortment.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Mr. Park, EVP, Samsung Cheil Industries</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Huge focus on online retailing as the market is at its infant stages and growing.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Department stores are focused on luxury and are largely competing with discount stores as each business model is affecting sales/profit of the opposition respectively.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Dr. Wu Jianzhong, Chairman, Wu Mart Stores Inc.</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Focused on improving their supply chain and logistics.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Current customers are people around each Wu Mart location.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Ideal customer includes some premium shoppers.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Wu Mart is expanding and developing specific stores that cater each segmentation respectively.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Wumart is in need of systems to track and understand their customers better.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Govind Shrikhande, Customer Care Associate &amp; Managing Director, Shopper’s Stop Ltd.</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Women are driving consumption in India.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Too many TV channels for effective channel marketing.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Main marketing channel focus lies within Indian newspaper and magazines.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Their vision and goal is to create family-oriented shops focused on customer satisfaction.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Facebook and Twitter are huge in India; thus, fueling innovation in the customer response area.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<h1>1130am-1230pm\r\nTopic: Industry Leaders Predict APAC’s Growth over the Next Three Years</h1><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Peter Sharp, Senior Vice President, Real Estate, New Business Planning, Mergers &amp; Acquisitions, Walmart Asia</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Focus is on Smart Choice stores in China.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Seen decent success with delis in Japan, might focus more attention on developing this area.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Utilize social networks, especially local ones (i.e. Kaixin, renren, youku, etc.).</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Can’t ignore women in senior management, 40% women at WRC.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Kal Patel, President Asia, Enterprise EVP, Best Buy</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ They are in love with China.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Trying to fall in love with India.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Best Buy was actually successful with the people in China.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Focused on moving forward with Five Star.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Now, physical stores compliment online stores and mobile stores.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<h1>130pm-230pm\r\nTopic: Understanding Asia’s Place in the Globalizing Retail World</h1><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Dr. Ira Kalish, Director of Global Research, Deloitte</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ India exports continue to rise.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Consumer spending won’t expand faster than GDP in India.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ India lacks a national market, too fragmented.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Michelle Leung, Head of Marketplace Development, eBay, Hong Kong</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Online comparison and research is high in Asia.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Consumers in Asia always search for the best price, check many sources.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Kal Patel, President Asia, Enterprise EVP, Best Buy</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Asia looks messy, but only to the ‘Western Eye’.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Word of mouth is what it’s all about in Asia. Take markets for example (i.e. Taiwan’s Guanghua Tech Market). People talk to each other to find what they want even though there are hundreds of small shops and they know where to get the best prices.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Focus on local ways and habits instead of fight them with arrogance. Instill these local ways into your business models.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ It’s obvious Asia isn’t one place. It’s many places and each has their own culture. Focus on localizing instead of trying to take something from abroad and trying to instill it into the market.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Building a brand, introducing and promoting a brand are totally different than building a business model. The brand is an idea. The business model is making the idea work locally.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ KFC is so successful because they’ve instilled the local culture into their business. It has an American face but a Chinese soul. Colonel on the outside, Chinese flavors on the inside.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Innovation is key to building winning strategies in foreign markets. You have to innovate to adapt.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Paul Martin, Commercial Director, Planet Retail</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Really understand the local market. Observe it. India example: Wet markets always price their onions cheaper than the hypermarkets to attract customers and avoid losing customers. It’s called the Onion Index.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Try, innovate, be prepared to make mistakes, learn from those mistakes and continue to innovate and try.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Reverse colonization is happening in Asia.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Mobile retail is the future for the industry.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<h1>230pm-320pm\r\nTopic: Creating Winning Retail Destinations</h1><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Simon Ho, CEO, CapitaMall Trust Management Limited</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Raffles City in Singapore is a huge success.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ They are taking the Raffles City concept to China and localizing the business model.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Match making ads on the streets is part of the local culture in Singapore. They captured this idea and held a match-making event in one of their malls. It was a huge success.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ It’s all about the retailers within their malls.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Vietnam market is not as open to foreign retailers.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Develop local partnerships to maneuver the market.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Lucy Wu Ruiling, Vice Secretary-General</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Focus on the hearts of the consumer.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Think development through wholly; consider things like mall architecture and appearance to lure customers in. Understand what the customer wants to build a complete customer experience.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Andrew Wu, Group Director, LVMH, China</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Product selection grows; thus, retail spectrum only grows, doesn’t shrink.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Focus on business model and understand local market.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Street door traffic doesn’t always equate to high sales/profit. They close their street doors off because their target customer enters the building from underground or another entrance. If their stores were as packed as someone else, they would be Carrefour.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Differentiate between store openings to capture time relevant factors/changes. People like change/different/freshness in Asia.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Tobias Wahmudt, Marketing Director, Spar International B.V.</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Focused on middle market, providing value buys for the general public.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Dr. Wu Jianzhong, Chairman, Wu Mart Stores Inc.</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Focused on creating a whole family experience within their shops.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ A lot of families spend all day outside. They want to create a place that provides, shopping, food, and entertainment for the family.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<h1>350pm-420pm\r\nTopic: World-class Customer Service</h1><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Li Weilong, Chairman, Xinglong Happy Family Business</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Launched customer service competitions within company to boost employee morale, motivation, improved customer experience/service.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Build relationships with customer in store through activities and creating a feeling of being part of a family.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<h1>420pm-5pm\r\nTopic: Capitalizing on the Ecommerce Opportunity</h1><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Jerry Black, Chief Strategy Officer, AEON; CEO, Asean; CIO and CEO, Digital Business</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Retail was driven by tech from 1995-2000.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ 2000-Now is business driven.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Imperative to focus on ‘bricks &amp; clicks’.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Business models focused around social media and its channels are the keys to success. Embrace and empower the customer.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Connect store managers with customers through mobile apps.</div><p align="left"></p>\r\n<h1>5pm-530pm\r\nTopic: Everything Has Changed – In-store Experiences Are Perfect for Building Meaningful Relationships with the Connected Consumer</h1><p align="left"></p>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Chris Aubrey, Vice President Global Retail Marketing, Adidas</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong><span style="color: #000000;">David Judge, Creative Director, Judge Gill</span></strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"><strong>Main Points</strong></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ It’s all about connected retail.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Focused on building relationships in store.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Working on Adiverse.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ They are against the ‘no photos’ theory. Why restrict the customer? Embrace the customer and what they are feeling and like to share with friends.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">+ Challenges lie within connecting the back-end systems.</div><p align="left"></p>', 'World Retail Congress Asia 2011 Recap', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'world-retail-congress-asia-2011-recap', '', '', '2013-02-20 03:26:04', '2013-02-20 07:26:04', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2154', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2204, 9, '2011-04-26 22:37:43', '2011-04-27 02:37:43', 'For those of you who couldn\'t make it to our seminar on April 13, 2011, here\'s a quick recap of what happened. We hope to see you at one of our upcoming events.\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Johnson Li</strong></span>\r\n<span style="color: #000000;">Chief Development Officer at Daphne International</span>\r\n\r\nRather than focusing on how to open a new store, Johnson Li from Daphne International presented problems encountered during site development. Johnson stated that developers are brand pioneers not brand users. Three layers surround a brand; city, trade zone, and site.\r\n\r\nFrom his understanding, development depends not only on experience but also scientific assessment approaches. He mentions that developers always face the problems of experimentalism, leading to project bottlenecks. Thus, the most important thing is meshing experiments with scientific judgment.\r\n\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2217" title="blog-quote-seminar-apr13-2011-johnson" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/blog-quote-seminar-apr13-2011-johnson.png" alt="" width="539" height="91" />\r\n\r\nWith regard to development uncertainties, Johnson talked about mastering methods of building multiple brands and managing different channels throughout development. The keys are to focus on brand positioning and understanding channel characteristics. The answer doesn\'t necessarily lie within how many stores you should open. Secondly, paying attention to the competitive situation of your trade areas sheds light on where you should develop your business. Market data helps understand the performance of your stores as well as any competitors nearby.\r\n\r\nAs for the most common developer problems and mistakes, Johnson emphasized that you must understand your competitors. Also, opening stores based on profit with a lack of brand concept is dangerous. Opening up an additional store just to increase your selling channels without a layout concept is just as detrimental to your business. People also lack research and data on business trade areas in regard to brands and consumers to fully understand a store\'s impact.\r\n\r\nLastly, Johnson pointed out that it\'s important to determine development priorities after you\'ve decided on your target cities.\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Ray Lei</strong></span>\r\n<span style="color: #000000;">Solution Director at Wincor Nixdorf</span>\r\n\r\nRay Lei from Wincor Nixdorf presented us with insight on how retailers are currently developing their businesses in China through the combination of info from ERP systems such as POS data with accurate market data. He pointed out that retailers didn\'t worry much about location 10 years ago since good sites were plentiful. However, the times have changed and now it\'s quite difficult to find the right location. "Location is money," said Ray.\r\n\r\nNow, retailers ask many questions. Is my location correct? Where are my competitors? How many stores do I need to open? What kind of store do I need to open? Ray stated that most retailers have ERP systems but they only provide internal information. Retailers lack market data. Furthermore, he said it\'s important to collect sales and market data to determine whether or not a location is good and if a business should open, close, or move stores. From experience, Ray specified that Wincor clients always want to get their hands on market data so they can combine it with data from their ERP systems.\r\n\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2219" title="blog-quote-seminar-apr13-2011-ray" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/blog-quote-seminar-apr13-2011-ray.png" alt="" width="539" height="91" />\r\n\r\nWith respect to tools and processes for store network success in China, Ray suggested four main points. The first is to really hone your data collection process. It includes being aware of sales data, customer data, as well as market data. Second, it\'s imperative to optimize your business intelligence analyses from cost savings, store spendings, sales rates, and competitor sales all the way through to market sales and rates.\r\n\r\nThe third point revolves around perseverance. Ray said that many opportunities come from the fact that you are in the market for a longer period of time over your competitors. His example of the Starbucks in Shanghai next to BinJiang University highlighted the 2 years it took to rise from earning less than 1,000RMB on its opening day to over 80,000RMB a day currently. The market data Starbucks acquired has played a part in creating the best performing store in China. Finally, Ray discussed the importance of comparing profit and gross margin with competitor and market data. Most importantly, businesses must understand the gross margins of its competitors and averages of the remaining market.\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Howard Hsiao</strong></span>\r\n<span style="color: #000000;">SVP, getchee Enterprise Solutions</span>\r\n\r\nHoward first briefed us with a little getchee history. However, his goal wasn\'t to talk about getchee\'s products and services but rather point out what it takes to build and manage a successful store network in China. We all know that the opportunities in China are grand and in order to seize them we must collect accurate industry-specific market data. Although data is the core of executing great expansion and optimization plans, it\'s the processes of collecting and analyzing the data that will foster profitable results.\r\n\r\nAdding to Johnson and Ray\'s points, Howard defined how to utilize tools to systematically and scientifically analyze data that integrates with sales performance and customer data. Moreover, Howard talked about how geospatial business tools play a key role in standardizing business management processes.\r\n\r\n<img class="aligncenter" title="blog-quote-seminar-apr13-2011-howard" src="../wp-content/uploads/2011/04/blog-quote-seminar-apr13-2011-howard.png" alt="" width="539" height="91" />\r\n\r\nThese types of tools have helped retailers answer problems across the board. In terms of expansion, it\'s important to first understand where your target customer segments are on city, district, and neighborhood levels. From here, you\'re able to prioritize market coverage to maximize revenue potential. Throughout this process, you pinpoint where your competitors are, determine the business potential of each store opening, as well as underline the positive and negative market factors that impact your business. These tools and systems also help manage your expansion operations by empowering your field teams\' decision-making processes.\r\n\r\nHoward also conveyed how geospatial business tools give organizations the power to map market characteristics that affect a store\'s profitability. More importantly, these kinds of tools map a competitor\'s current network strategy and coverage.\r\n\r\nFinally, Howard focused on operations management and what it takes to systematically develop optimal pricing strategies across different markets within a region. It\'s no coincidence that the process comes full circle and lands back at the home of analyzing data to determine optimal product mixes with respect to various trade zones, seasons, and time sensitivities. The process obviously doesn\'t stop there as Howard emphasized how to use tools to test effectiveness of marketing campaigns by mapping all this information to visually understand spatial relationships. Ultimately, these are the methods to combine accurate market data with business performance data to make profitable development and operational decisions.\r\n\r\nPresentation slides are available. To receive a copy or to schedule a meeting, please call us at +886.2.77122.3600 or send an email to <a href="mailto:edward.eng@getchee.com">edward.eng@getchee.com</a>.', 'Seminar Recap - Tools & Processes for Store Network Success in China', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'seminar-recap-tools-processes-for-store-network-success-in-china', '', '', '2013-02-20 03:26:04', '2013-02-20 07:26:04', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2204', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2226, 9, '2011-05-11 21:52:58', '2011-05-12 01:52:58', 'Bruce Berkman, CEO of <em>getchee</em>, will facilitate a breakfast roundtable where he will bring up the difficulties of expanding a business in China. Bruce will also open up the doors to people who have problems with managing a network of stores. There will be four scenarios to choose from to create a valuable discussion.\r\n\r\n<strong>Scenario 1</strong>\r\nI have 10 stores. A majority of them are making a profit. Should I open more stores? If so, how many stores should I open and where? How do I expand efficiently?\r\n\r\n<strong>Scenario 2</strong>\r\nI\'m rolling out a line of products. I want to sell them in my own stores and other shops. How do I efficiently manage distribution? How do I market the products and track campaign success?\r\n\r\n<strong>Scenario 3</strong>\r\nI manage a network of 20 stores. Five of the stores are not performing well. How do I pinpoint the causes of these underperforming assets? What corrective steps do I take?\r\n\r\n<strong>Scenario 4</strong>\r\nI manage a network of stores in the States. I want to expand in other markets like China, India, and Vietnam. How do I find the path of least resistance?\r\n\r\n<em>Look for Bruce Berkman\'s table under the Sustainability or Development category on Monday, May 23, 2011 from 630am-830am in the North Hall, Room N1.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Emerging Market Insight at ICSC RECon \'11</strong>\r\nVisit our booth and talk about the tremendous opportunities in Asia. Also, understand what kind of problems retailers are facing in China, India, and Southeast Asia. We\'ll share our experience and knowledge on building and optimizing store networks in emerging Asian economies.\r\n\r\n<strong>Save Time, Schedule a Meeting in Advance</strong>\r\nWe\'re happy to speak to you in person about any problems or questions you have in regard to markets in Asia. We always want to provide valuable information to anyone we speak with. Contact <a title="I\'d like to schedule a private Q/A session at ICSC RECon 2011 in advance." href="mailto:edward.eng@getchee.com" target="_blank">Edward Eng</a> to schedule a private Q&amp;A session at ICSC.\r\n\r\n<strong>Shortcut to Our Booth</strong>\r\n+ Booth S7426\r\n+ W Street &amp; 74th Avenue\r\n+ Find getchee on the <a title="getchee\'s ICSC Booth Location" href="http://exhibits.icsc.org/2011sc/public/floorplan.aspx?MapID=111&amp;BoothID=138259&amp;Booth=S7426" target="_blank">ICSC RECon 2011 map</a>\r\n\r\n<strong>General ICSC RECon 2011 Info</strong>\r\n+ May 22-25, 2011\r\n+ Las Vegas Convention Center in Las Vegas, NV\r\n+ <a title="ICSC RECon 2011 Website" href="http://www.icsc.org/2011SC/" target="_blank">ICSC RECon 2011 website</a>', 'Meet CEO of getchee at ICSC 2011', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'meet-ceo-of-getchee-at-icsc-2011', '', '', '2013-02-20 03:26:04', '2013-02-20 07:26:04', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2226', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
