INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2286, 9, '2011-06-13 21:56:23', '2011-06-14 01:56:23', 'We are hosting monthly networking events in Shanghai on the third Wednesday of every month. Join us for drinks and finger food while you mingle with professionals from multiple industries. Business managers, owners, expatriates, and friends are all welcome. Don\'t forget your business cards.\r\n\r\n<strong>Who is getchee?</strong>\r\n<em>getchee</em>\'s the only on-demand provider of Asian market intelligence to businesses looking to invest in emerging markets. We provide access to hard-to-find market data and analytics in the rapidly growing markets of China, India, and S.E. Asia . We\'ve helped dozens of large retail, banking, and automotive brands successfully expand and optimize their store networks in Asia.\r\n\r\n<iframe align="center" src="http://www.flickr.com/slideShow/index.gne?set_id=72157626631453915" width="517" height="517" frameBorder="0" scrolling="no"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<strong>Register for Event</strong>\r\nDate: June 15, 2011 (Wed.)\r\nCheck-in: 6:00p.m. to 7:00p.m.\r\nActivities &amp; Topics: 7:00p.m. to 9:00p.m.\r\nVenue: JoVino\r\nAddress: No. 527, North Shaan Xi Road, Shanghai, China\r\nDress Code: Business Casual\r\nRegistration Fee: Free with RSVP before 1p.m. on June 15.\r\nFeel free to forward this invitation to interested third parties.\r\n<a title="getchee Events - Retail Pro Meetup June 15, 2011" href="http://events.getchee.com/networking-event-jun2011/index.html?utm_source=blog%2Brpm%2Bjun15%2B2011%2Bevents%2Blink&amp;utm_medium=blog%2Brpm%2Bjun15%2B2011%2Bevents%2Blink&amp;utm_campaign=blog%2Brpm%2Bjun15%2B2011%2Bevents%2Blink" target="_blank">Register here</a>.\r\n\r\n<strong>You &amp; getchee</strong>\r\nIf you are interested in becoming a sponsor or guest speaking at one of our events, please contact <a href="mailto:edward.eng@getchee.com" target="_blank">Edward Eng</a> for details.', 'Retail Pro Meetup - June 15, 2011', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'retail-pro-meetup-june-15-2011', '', '', '2013-02-20 03:26:04', '2013-02-20 07:26:04', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2286', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2319, 12, '2011-06-21 02:09:17', '2011-06-21 06:09:17', '<a title="HSBC Ranks Thailand #1" href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/expatviewThaland.png" target="_blank"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2339" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/expatviewThaland.png" alt="" width="539" height="310" /></a>\r\n\r\nHSBC has ranked the current quality of living in 25 countries according to the opinions of expats living abroad. Seven of them are getchee markets.\r\n\r\nThe <a href="http://expatexplorer.hsbc.com/" target="_blank">HSBC interactive world map</a> is based on a large survey of 4,000 expats conducted in 2010. Individual criteria can be selected under the broad categories of economic well-being, lifestyle and experience, and the well-being of children to contrast the performance of different countries.\r\n\r\nIn terms of expat living experience in getchee market countries that include factors like enjoying local food, ability to make local friends, and finding accommodation, HSBC ranked Thailand 1<sup>st</sup> Malaysia 9<sup>th</sup>, and China 21<sup>st</sup>.\r\n\r\nWhen including economic data like size of property, income, and health care costs along with experience, HSBC ranked Thailand at 4<sup>th</sup> and Singapore 3<sup>rd</sup>.\r\n\r\nWhen looking at all factors including economic data, experience, and ratings on how good a country is to raise your children, Singapore ranked 1<sup>st</sup> with Hong Kong in 2<sup>nd</sup>.', 'HSBC Ranks Thailand #1', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'hsbc-ranks-thailand-1', '', '', '2013-02-25 04:40:17', '2013-02-25 08:40:17', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2319', 0, 'post', '', 2, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2352, 12, '2011-06-21 23:48:39', '2011-06-22 03:48:39', '<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/madeforChina2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2372" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/madeforChina2-e1308735551535.jpg" alt="" width="515" height="287" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a title="Trendwatching" href="http://www.trendwatching.com/" target="_blank"><span><span>Trendwatching</span></span></a>, a global trending firm wrote about a new trend in China that finds more and more "western" brands catering to the specific taste and styles of Chinese consumers instead of just importing already developed products that only have "western" tastes in mind.\r\n\r\n<span>Not only do consumers in China naturally appreciate custom goods that are designed with their tastes in mind, but also have a desire for products that consider their own unique needs (smaller shapes, sizes, <span>etc</span>. ). The drive can also be be attributed to massive amounts of Chinese pride. </span>\r\n\r\n"The pride of the Chinese people - pride in their country, heritage, history, economic power, and personal and social freedoms, their growing international importance, and yes, their growing military strength - is a fundamental characteristic of China that one encounters over and over and over again." - Robert Lawrence Kuhn\r\n\r\n<strong><span style="font-weight: normal;"><span><span>Trendwatching</span> claims that this phenomenon is just one of many similar trends <span>prompted</span> by the continual economic power shifting towards emerging markets. They continue with providing some interesting stats on the area:</span></span></strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>China\'s retail sales, the main gauge of consumer spending, rose 18.7% year on year to USD 183 billion in May 2010, following a 15.2% rise the previous year.\r\n(Source: Chinese National Bureau of Statistics, June 2010)</li>\r\n	<li>China’s retail sales may outstrip those of the US by reaching USD 5 trillion in 2016.\r\n(Source: Chinese People’s Political Consultative Conference, September 2010)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nBelow is a list of some of the brands who are already doing this, either by creating new "China-specific" brands or by creating products specifically with Chinese consumers in mind:\r\n\r\n<a title="dENIZEN Jeans from Levi\'s" href="http://www.levistrauss.com/brands/denizen" target="_blank"><span><span>dENIZEN</span></span></a> jeans from Levis, <a title="Shang Xia from Hemes" href="http://www.shang-xia.com/" target="_blank"><span><span>Shang</span> <span>Xia</span></span></a> from Hermes, <a title="Dior Blue Phone" href="http://red-luxury.com/2010/09/08/dior-shanghai-blue-phone/" target="_blank">Dior</a>,  <a title="Chloe Handbag" href="http://www.jingdaily.com/en/luxury/chloe-celebrates-five-years-in-china-with-limited-edition-handbag/" target="_blank">Chloe,</a> <a title="BMW M3 Tiger" href="http://www.bmwblog.com/2010/08/31/more-photos-of-the-bmw-m3-tiger-edition/" target="_blank">BMW</a>', 'Creating for China, Not Just In', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', '2352', '', 'http://red-luxury.com/2010/09/08/dior-shanghai-blue-phone/\nhttp://www.bmwblog.com/2010/08/31/more-photos-of-the-bmw-m3-tiger-edition/', '2013-02-25 04:40:17', '2013-02-25 08:40:17', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2352', 0, 'post', '', 2, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2376, 12, '2011-06-23 02:10:10', '2011-06-23 06:10:10', 'The Wall Street Journal recently spoke to Professor John Quelch of the China Europe International Business School about the five myths and common misconceptions he\'s identified about business in China.\r\n\r\n<a title="Chinese Consumers Don\'t Consume!" href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/1.jpg" target="_blank"></a><a title="Chinese Consumers Don\'t Consume!" href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/11.jpg" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-2442" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/11.jpg" alt="" width="250" height="120" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\nNOT TRUE:</strong> Soon China will become the number one market in the world for luxury brands! Did you know that right now more Ferraris are sold in China then anywhere else in the world?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a title="Chinese Consumers Aren\'t Social!" href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/2.jpg" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-2378" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/2.jpg" alt="" width="250" height="120" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\nNOT TRUE:</strong> A recent TNS study revealed that 265 million Chinese engage in social media, on average, 5.6 hours per week, 54% of them use a service daily!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a title="Chinese Can Imitate But Not Innovate!" href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/3.jpg" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-2379" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/3.jpg" alt="" width="250" height="120" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\nNOT TRUE:</strong> Chinese universities have been producing more science and engineering PhDs then ever before! Plus a large amount of Chinese have been trained oversees and are ready to innovate!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a title="Chinese Managers Won\'t Go Global!" href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/4.jpg" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-2380" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/4.jpg" alt="" width="250" height="120" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\nNOT TRUE:</strong> The number of Chinese currently studying English is five times the total population of the UK!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a title="Chinese Students Are Passive!" href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/5.jpg" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-2381" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/5.jpg" alt="" width="250" height="120" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\nNOT TRUE:</strong> Recent global high school scores placed Shanghai students number one in mathematics, science, and other subjects. You can\'t get there from being passive.\r\nSource: <a title="The Wall Street Journal" href="http://blogs.wsj.com/source/2011/06/19/five-myths-about-business-in-china/" target="_blank">The Wall Street Journal</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Five Business Myths in China', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'five-business-myths-in-china', '', '', '2013-02-25 04:40:17', '2013-02-25 08:40:17', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2376', 0, 'post', '', 3, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2446, 12, '2011-06-26 22:51:11', '2011-06-27 02:51:11', 'The public out cry against corruption by officials in China is apparently becoming loud enough for the communist party to pledge action.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/asiapcf/06/25/china.corruption/index.html" target="_blank">CNN</a> reports on the communist party stated commitment, and published a long list of high ranking officials and public figures who have been prosecuted and punished harshly, including Li Peiying, former president of the Capital Airports Holding Company,  who was executed after he was convicted of receiving 26.61 million yuan (US$4.1 million) in bribes.\r\n\r\nThe real estate market in China has historically been entrenched in corruption which has made the job of expanding networks in China all the more costly for companies.', 'Communist Party Controlling Corruption', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'communist-party-pledges-crack-down-on-corruption', '', '', '2013-02-25 04:40:17', '2013-02-25 08:40:17', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2446', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2456, 12, '2011-06-28 23:58:57', '2011-06-29 03:58:57', '<span>NPR\'s recently aired "talk of the nation" program discusses China\'s economic transformation and ways they\'re increasing their international profile and what it means for the world.</span>\r\n\r\n<a title="NPR : China\'s Growing Reach" href="http://www.npr.org/2011/06/27/137451465/chinas-growing-reach-spans-continents" target="_blank">Listen to the podcast here.</a>', 'NPR : China\'s Growing Reach', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'npr-chinas-growing-reach', '', '', '2013-02-25 04:40:16', '2013-02-25 08:40:16', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2456', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2474, 12, '2011-06-30 23:10:18', '2011-07-01 03:10:18', '<span>Taking effect today, foreign workers living and working in mainland China will receive medical, work injury, retirement, unemployment, and maternity benefits just like their Chinese co-workers. Expats wanting coverage will have to pay a percentage of their wages for the program. While the exact details have yet to be disclosed, most people feel it will be similar to what Chinese workers currently pay, which is about 11% of their total monthly income.</span>\r\n\r\nAccording to <a title="Social Security Set to Cover Foreign Workers " href="http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2011-06/29/content_12797988.htm" target="_blank">China Daily</a>, 58 percent of 164 foreign respondents said they were willing to participate in the program. However, there are many concerns about the new program including doubts about how well the program will be managed, details about benefits, and the impact of higher cost to employers and foreign companies doing business in China. The program is seem as a positive addition for foreigners who plan to stay in China long term and possibly even after retirement . Some workers also feel the program will allow them better access to cheaper more efficient medical services and programs while living and working in China.', 'China Gives Expats Social Security', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'china-gives-expats-social-security', '', '', '2013-02-25 04:40:16', '2013-02-25 08:40:16', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2474', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2490, 12, '2011-07-04 05:37:56', '2011-07-04 09:37:56', '<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2544" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/sevenCities1.jpg"/>\r\n\r\nThe City of Shanghai recently held a news conference to announce their long-term\r\nplan to develop seven new suburban cities with the intention of balancing urban and\r\nrural development, and providing some population relief for the crowded city center.\r\n<span> The biggest of the seven new cities, <span>Songjiang</span> New City plans to have 1.1 million</span>\r\nresidents in the area.\r\n\r\n"We are trying to attract more residents with convenient transport networks, including\r\n<span> high-speed railway and other rail transitions as well as better job opportunities after</span>\r\n<span> the launch of industrial bases," said <span>Hu</span> Jun, deputy director of the Shanghai Municipal</span>\r\nPlanning, Landand Resources Administration.\r\n\r\n<span><span>Hu</span> said the quality of life in the suburbs would be as good as that in the urban center,</span>\r\n<span> with a variety of public service resources, convenient transport and environmentally</span>\r\nsensitive construction.\r\n\r\n<strong><span>The development of these new cities could have a number of possible impacts:</span></strong>\r\n<strong>1.</strong> Demographic shifts as people move from city center outward\r\n<strong>2.</strong> Real estate market impacts as new locations open and old locations change\r\n<strong>3.</strong> New market locations for goods and services\r\n<strong>4.</strong> Shifts in living standards for new residence with new found expendable incomes\r\n\r\nVisit <em><a title="getchee - Be Market Intelligent" href="http://www.getchee.com/" target="_blank">getchee</a></em> to see how we address these issues and more\r\n\r\nSource: <a title="China Daily" href="http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2011-06/30/content_12805181.htm" target="_blank"><span><span>China Daily</span></span></a>', 'Seven New Cities, One Big Shanghai', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'seven-new-cities-one-big-shanghai', '', '', '2013-02-25 04:40:16', '2013-02-25 08:40:16', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2490', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2552, 12, '2011-07-07 03:09:31', '2011-07-07 07:09:31', '<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2555" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/suberbia.jpg" alt="china builds suburbs getchee" width="517" height="350" />\r\n\r\nItalian castles, Dutch villas, American suburbs, you name it, China\'s either already got it, or they\'re working on it. The explosion of  travel hungry Chinese has led to a drive to re-create famous towns and architecture found in Europe and throughout the Americas.\r\n\r\nOne of the more popular examples of this is <a title="Thames Town in Shanghai - Shanghai Virtual Tourism" href="http://www.360kk.org/shanghai/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=48:thames-town&amp;catid=25:scenic-spots-in-shanghai&amp;Itemid=2" target="_blank">Thames Town</a>. Built just outside of Shanghai, the Small river side town features street names like Oxford, Queen, and High Street. There\'s cobbled roads, red telephone booths, Victorian terraces, a main square, and a man-made Thames river. If it weren\'t for a few of the high-rise developments seen off in the distance, you would swear you were in an old English village.\r\n\r\nAlso being replicated in spite of much controversy is the entire UNESCO world heritage town of Hallstatt in Central Austria. The new Chinese Hallstatt being called "Hallstatt See".  Located in Huizhou in Guangdong province, it will feature precise replication of the original, even down to the style of the doorknobs.\r\n\r\nChina is building America too. Outside Beijing and Shanghai, tract-home developments designed to mimic Spanish, Italian, Victorian as well as simple cookie-cutter style architecture have all-American names: Yosemite and Napa Valley. But its not just the name they want. "Chinese want the whole package, the three-car garage, the mall, all of that." - <a title="Modern Suburbia not Just in America Anymore" href="http://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2008-04-15-suburbia_N.htm" target="_blank">Usa Today</a>\r\n\r\nIt\'s not just towns with cultural significance either. Recently a Chinese developer announced he would replicate the entire  home town of Salvador Dali. The town, which will be built in Xiamen bay hopes to be popular with Chinese who want to experience Spanish culture in their own backyard, and without shelling out the big bucks for the plane ticket.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>getchee </em>Commentary</strong>\r\n1. Maybe China wants to keep its dollars in China? Instead of people flying oversees to shop and buy things, they can visit exact replicas of these places. They gain a very similar experience while spending less money; not to mention, it\'s money spent in China.\r\n2. What does this mean for retailers? Will there be a drive for store fronts and goods that mimic overseas cultural experiences in new and unique ways? Opportunity to mimic hometown surroundings; resurgence of American strip malls in China?', 'Why go west? China builds their own...', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'why-go-west-china-builds-their-own', '', '', '2013-02-25 04:40:16', '2013-02-25 08:40:16', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2552', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2585, 12, '2011-07-13 21:51:18', '2011-07-14 01:51:18', 'In a recent move that could see the exports to Pakistan from India increase, Pakistan has granted India MFN (most favored nation) status. Not only could the move increase India\'s exports, but it could save over $1.5 billion annually through the redirection of import items like pharmaceuticals, chemicals, steel, and processed foods. In a joint statement released last week, industry captains suggested that Pakistan granted MFN status to India for expanding bilateral trade. According to reports, Pakistan is paying 35% extra cost on trade logistics through third countries and illegal channels. The MFN status would allow Pakistan to directly import such products from India. Current trade between the two countries stands at $ 2.5 billion, with thousands items being traded between them.\r\n\r\nSource: <a href="http://www.financialexpress.com/" target="_blank">The Financial Express</a>', 'India - "Most-Favored Nation"', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'india-most-favored-nation', '', '', '2013-02-25 04:40:16', '2013-02-25 08:40:16', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2585', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2603, 12, '2011-07-18 01:56:27', '2011-07-18 05:56:27', '<a href="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/kapakCity3.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2615" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/kapakCity3.jpg" alt="" width="517" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nA new Chinese city being built in northern Loas on the Mekong River across from Thailand, may become the new Chinese Vegas. Kapok city, which currently can\'t be found on any maps will feature casinos, hotels, an international airport, up to six golf courses, residences, shopping malls, markets, restaurants, and bars. The 25,000 acre area was leased by the Laotian government to Chinese business group Kings Romans for 100 years, and although the city is technically in Laos the currency used is Chinese RMB and the official language is Mandarin. Currently, most tourist to the area are Chinese, but hopes are to attract more Western and Southeast Asian tourists. The city is expected to become the second largest city in Laos, bigger then the world heritage city of Luang Prabang, and a bigger gambling destination then the current hotspot of Macau.', 'China\'s Hidden Vegas', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'chinas-hidden-vegas', '', '', '2013-02-25 04:40:16', '2013-02-25 08:40:16', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2603', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
