INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2673, 12, '2011-08-09 04:58:23', '2011-08-09 08:58:23', '<h1>Understanding Cultural Differences</h1>\r\nChina is currently the fastest growing market in the world with an average annual GDP growth of 8%. In addition, China’s gross domestic product reached RMB 20.94 trillion in 2006. With this rapid economic growth, more foreign companies than ever before are looking to enter China to expand their brands. Compared to other developing nations, China has the highest foreign investment today. China received a total of 622.4 billion U.S. dollars in foreign direct investment from 1979 to 2005. If China continues to progress at this rate, many believe that China will soon be the largest world economy.\r\n<div class="callout">In part one of our five part series we\'ll talk about cultural differences foreign companies face when entering China.</div>\r\nUnderstanding cultural differences should be one of the highest priorities when entering any foreign country, but these difference aren\'t always given the attention they deserve, or are even completely ignored which can lead to huge problems both immediate and down the road. Here are a few of some of the most commonly known cultural differences that businesses entering china are bound to run into and some ideas on how to work with them, not against them.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Language</strong> – While it\'s true that many if not most Chinese professionals now speak decent English, the language barrier can still be a huge issue for many foreign companies looking to enter the Chinese market. Many locals in China are still unable to communicate fluently and extensively in English, and most foreigners are unable to speak the Chinese language. In order to do good, effective business in China, as in any country, the involved parties need to have clear communication.\r\n\r\nHiring the help of good interpreters and who can not only speak the language but who are also familiar with the Chinese culture and that of the foreign companies is a high priority. Some companies hire both Chinese translators and westerners with fluency so that communications are understood from both cultural perspectives. Many companies also sponsor Chinese language lessons for those who will be spending the most time there.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2811" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/meeting1.jpg" alt="social networking in Shanghai" width="518" height="335" />\r\n\r\n<strong>Guanxi / Business Socializing</strong> – Doing business in China usually involves a lot more socializing then westerners are used to. This is called building "Guanxi" and by getting the right "Guanxi", businesses minimize the risks when doing business in China. To do this, business often takes a back seat to getting to know each other better, even if it means a delay to the deal. Foreigners might think that socializing is a waste of time, but to the Chinese it\'s a part of doing business, as a result foreigners should develop their own "Guanxi" networks when expanding in China.\r\n\r\n<strong>Face / Reputation</strong> – Reputation of the individual is very important in China. If an action will humiliate someone or ruin a reputation, it is avoided. When shame occurs, the person sacrifices their job or whatever it is that will heal the shame.  In the west, reputations come and go overnight and in the end usually does not matter. The end result is more of the focus. A person is more likely to overlook a reputation to get the job done. Not so for the Chinese. When doing business in China pay close attention to what you do and say and how it impacts "face". Be very sensitive to how your actions impact the way the other person might be perceived.\r\n\r\n<strong>Confrontation / Conflict</strong> – If you are planning on conducting business in China or expecting an extended stay, it might be useful to know that the direct way that most westerners approach issues is not the way to go in China. Direct conflict or confrontation over issues is looked down on. It doesn\'t matter that the “truth” needs to be spoken, respect and honor to each person is more important than that. To prove a point and show yourself in the right even over business issues is considered shameful and should be avoided. This ties in closely with "face" in that causing conflict is bound to give someone bad "face" which is to be avoided. You might disagree with something, or someone, but try to communicate your ideas in a way that is friendly and not abrasive, and in a way that doesn\'t say, "I\'m right and you\'re wrong".\r\n\r\n<strong>Time Sensitivity</strong> – Crossing cultures for business can be frustrating when it interferes with getting the job done.  Most westerners are very time sensitive when it comes to meetings and deadlines. If the meeting is to begin at 2:00, then everyone should be there at that time. The Chinese don\'t view time as an absolute but more as a suggestion. Concern is not expressed for a meeting starting late or ending at a different time. The same can be applied to deadlines. If a report is due on Friday, a westerner would be waiting for that report to be received before end of business day. The Chinese would not worry if it showed up several days later. Learning to be more flexible when it comes to your time might seem like your losing time, or even wasting it. But when working in China you\'ll quickly find out that here, time spent, is time gained. Without the time, "guanxi" can\'t be built, and without the "guanxi" you\'ll have a more difficult time building your business.\r\n\r\nThese are just a few of the most common cultural differences companies should be aware of when entering China. Consideration should be given to doing more thorough research in order to build cultural awareness within your organization. Taking the time to acknowledge these differences will help you greatly in the long run to building better business relationships, and a better business in China.\r\n<h3><strong>Read part 2 of <em>Bringing your brand to China: </em><a title="Bringing Your Brand to China – Part 2" href="http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2875">Understanding market differences</a></strong></h3>', 'Bringing Your Brand to China - Part 1', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'so-you-want-to-expand-your-brand-into-china-part-1-understanding-differences', '', '\nhttp://blog.getchee.com/?p=2875', '2013-02-20 03:24:38', '2013-02-20 07:24:38', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2673', 0, 'post', '', 3, ''); 
