INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2875, 12, '2011-08-29 23:26:37', '2011-08-30 03:26:37', '<h2>Market differences</h2>\r\nThe concept of shopping for a product can appear to be universal, but along with cultural differences comes market differences and shopping habit differences. In part two of ‘<a title="Bringing Your Brand to China - Part 1" href="http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2673" target="_blank">Bringing Your Brand to China</a>’, we’ve presented examples of how the shopping habits and environments differ in China compared to the rest of the world.\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Haggling/Bartering</strong> - In the West, it’s more common for the sticker price to be the final price. Suggesting a lower one to the sales clerk would probably be met with a blank stare. However, in China virtually everything is negotiable, from bowls and cups to clothes and cars. Negotiation or bartering can be quick, but often tends to be a long drawn out process weighing in everything from the quality to the relationship or ‘Guanxi’ the buyer has with the seller.\r\n\r\nBartering is a fine skill that most Chinese have grown up perfecting, both on the buyer side and the seller side, and they are used to doing it. Bartering culture may be more prevalent in traditional markets and local business, but the concept often extends to many brand stores as well who will offer unadvertised discounts to customers who ask for them or those who are frequent shoppers. Unlike loyalty programs in the West that are heavily marketed, these discounts might not even be advertised which allows employees to give the discount on a shopper by shopper basis. This creates a highly personal shopping experience that reflects the historical shopping engagement found at a local market. Businesses entering China should take into consideration the traditional Chinese shopping experience when designing marketing and sales programs.\r\n\r\n<strong>2. <em>getchee</em>s</strong> – The name of our company actually takes its name from this Taiwanese word that refers to areas made up of a lot of stores all selling similar merchandise. Many cities in the world have such <em>getchee</em>s, but none more than China. In China, opening a new tea shop right across the street from your friend’s tea shop is seen less as a faux pas and more of an expectation. In China, people enjoy shopping in areas they know sell similar products, so they can shop, compare, and barter all in one place. So when opening a new store, it’s not necessarily a bad thing to have your competition near you or in some cases right next to you. What\'s important to know is the market capacity in the locations you plan to enter so that you can make critical network strategy decisions.\r\n\r\n<strong>3. Cash is king</strong> - The trend in the West has been a shift to a paper-less economy with most people using credit cards and debit cards combined with online banking to fulfill most of their daily transactions. This makes it easy for businesses and banks to keep track of transaction data. While the use of plastic is slowly growing in China, the majority of people still use cash every day. This means that accounting data is slightly more difficult to process and disseminate.\r\n\r\n<strong>4. More</strong>- Along with more people living in more densely compacted cities comes more traffic, noises, signage, and distractions. Building a brand in China means you need to compete not only with all your competitors, but with a distracting environment as well. Chinese people living in the cities are accustomed to this, but for foreign companies, knowing how to position their brand and the stores that support them appropriately is a challenge. However, it’s one key to your success in China.\r\n\r\nReaching Chinese customers is about recognizing the fact that there are many variables to consider, each of which can be specific to their industries. It\'s not good enough to just be aware of cultural differences and market differences. Companies need to study the particulars within their target markets. General business rules apply or course, and companies looking to break into the Chinese markets need to compete in one or more of the following categories…\r\n\r\nBrand: Well established multinational companies have an advantage when it comes to selling in China. Just like people everywhere else, the Chinese are influenced by what they see on TV and in movies. To the average person, a can of Coke is more appealing than an unknown brand of cola because he or she feels more certain about what to expect from the experience.\r\n\r\n<a title="Coca-Cola\'s Growth in China" href="http://blog.getchee.com/?p=711" target="_blank">What about Coca-Cola\'s growth in China?</a>\r\n\r\nQuality: Companies that make products that are better than what is already on the market tend to do well in China. People who have the money are willing to pay more for quality when they can clearly see a difference. For example, Japanese and American cars are very common on city streets throughout China. This is the case even when their prices are significantly higher than Chinese-made cars that have a poor reputation for quality.\r\n\r\nPrice: Foreign companies that make products that can compete on price against their Chinese counterparts will likely do well.  However, this is not easy. Most products made by international companies, even when produced in China, are more expensive. The trick is to price them within a reaching point of Chinese brands.  If a foreign product is not much more expensive, then people will likely give it a try even if it is not a well-known brand. The still-prevailing-perception is non-Chinese products are better quality.\r\n\r\nForeign brands in China have a greater chance of succeeding if they recognize market and shopping habit differences and adapt appropriately in a category they can compete in. It\'s important that brands looking to enter China recognize…\r\n\r\n1. China is no longer a country of cheap brands. Domestic companies have increased their technology and marketing skills by working with foreign companies.\r\n\r\n<a title="5 Business Myths in China" href="http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2376" target="_blank">Learn about 5 business myths in China.</a>\r\n\r\n2. While foreign brand names do well in China, Chinese have a very strong sense of national pride too. Products shouldn\'t feel too foreign. Marketing heads need to find locals to work with who understand Chinese culture and how people feel toward a particular product. This will help drive your marketing path.\r\n\r\n<a title="Made for China" href="http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2352" target="_blank">Read "Made for China" for closer look at this.</a>\r\n\r\n3. The Chinese government is not easy to communicate with and confusing for foreign companies who are unaccustomed to its processes. It\'s important to find locals that have a good relationship with the authorities to ensure things go faster and smoother.\r\n<h3><strong>Read part 3 of <em>Bringing your brand to China: <a title="Bring your brand to China – part 3" href="http://blog.getchee.com/?p=3057">Brand ownership and rights</a></em></strong></h3>', 'Bringing Your Brand to China - Part 2', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'bringing-your-brand-to-china-part-2', '', 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2673\nhttp://blog.getchee.com/?p=2352\nhttp://blog.getchee.com/?p=711\nhttp://blog.getchee.com/?p=2376\nhttp://blog.getchee.com/?p=3057', '2013-02-20 03:24:07', '2013-02-20 07:24:07', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2875', 0, 'post', '', 1, ''); 
