INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (3090, 12, '2011-11-17 03:28:00', '2011-11-17 07:28:00', '<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="size-full wp-image-3097 aligncenter" title="ME" src="http://blog.getchee.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/ME.jpg" alt="" width="448" height="299" /></p>\r\nThis year\'s <a href="http://www.marcusevans.com/" target="_blank">Marcus Evans</a> event brought together a compelling variety of retail professionals from a mixture of industries and functions to talk about people and stores. A few of the stand out presentations include:\r\n\r\nStore Network Management - <a href="http://shop.mango.com/home.faces?state=she_736_IN" target="_blank">Mango</a>\r\nMerchandising - <a href="http://www.zegna.com/" target="_blank">Ermenigildo Zegna\r\n</a>Distributor Performance Tracking - <a href="http://www.nike.com/nikeos/p/nike/language_select/" target="_blank">Nike\r\n</a> INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (3120, 12, '2011-12-05 22:48:08', '2011-12-06 02:48:08', '<h1>Deciding on Locations</h1>\r\nSo you\'ve decided to bring your brand to China. You\'ve done research and gained knowledge about <a title="Bringing Your Brand to China – Part 1" href="http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2673" target="_blank">culture</a> and <a title="Bringing Your Brand to China – Part 2" href="http://blog.getchee.com/?p=2875" target="_blank">market differences</a>, you have some better ideas about how to protect your <a title="Bringing Your Brand to China – Part 3" href="http://blog.getchee.com/?p=3057" target="_blank">brand and intellectual rights</a>, and now you need to think about where exactly you should be setting up new locations. While the key to answering these types of questions usually involves the use of relevant and accurate data, there are a number of steps companies can initiate on their way to finding locations. Your company may be considering a variety of location types but we\'ll address the three big ones: factories, offices, and stores.\r\n<h2><strong>Locations for Your Factories</strong></h2>\r\n<strong></strong>Getting the location of your factory right is not such a big issue if you are outsourcing - the Chinese factory owner has to cover most location-related issues. However, it\'s probably the biggest single issue if you are planning to build or buy a factory. Getting your location wrong can be costly. Factors you should consider regarding where to build your factory include:\r\n\r\n• How good is the local infrastructure; e.g. electricity supply, etc.\r\n• How close is the support structure, the availability of skilled workers, and technical experts\r\n• How good is the local logistics system\r\n\r\nLocating in special economic zones usually offers financial incentives and assist in managing utilities, logistics, and factory support. The cost could be higher but worth it in the long run.\r\n<h2><strong>Locations for Your Office</strong></h2>\r\nIn most cities, there is a glut of available office spaces, but making the right choice isn\'t always easy. Here are a few things to think about when considering where to put your office location:\r\n<h3>Consider Transportation Convenience</h3>\r\nThis can be important for newly arriving companies who need their people to have easy access to trading partners. Some experts have suggested that having transportation advantages is more valuable then the visible advantages of being situated in city centers.\r\n<h3>Choose the Correct Region</h3>\r\nIt’s important to be in the appropriate region for your business and to be near those types of companies which you do business with most. In China, even more than the west, business organizations group together in tightly knit areas and regions. This makes building "guanxi" easier and more convenient.\r\n<h3>Forecast the Future</h3>\r\nDo some preparation to make sure you won\'t have to do another move too soon after  your initial one. Otherwise, things could become costlier than expected.\r\n<h2><strong>Locations for Your Stores</strong></h2>\r\nThis is usually one of the most difficult tasks for large retailers and banks with ATM networks. With over 160 cities in China each containing over a million people, the options can seem daunting. Entering China via the 5 largest cities is not always the best model.  These markets are more mature, more expensive, have greater brand awareness, and can only be quickly entered once brand awareness is established.  Some companies start in tier 2-4 cities and build their brand and resources before rapidly expanding – successfully - into the largest markets as a more localized brand.  Every good idea can be copied and cheaply reproduced quickly – and Chinese consumers do watch pricing.  Some of the secondary markets (i.e. Chengdu and Zhejiang province cities) have very large disposable incomes and tastes for western goods, but are overlooked initially.  They shouldn\'t be. Here\'s a few tips for getting your locations right.\r\n<h3>Target Your Market</h3>\r\nWho are your customers and why do they buy from you? Look for common characteristics and interests. Which ones bring in the most business? Don\'t just think about who has a need for your product, but who is most likely to buy it. Most markets can be broken down into the following types of factors:\r\n\r\nAge\r\nLocation\r\nGender\r\nIncome Level\r\nEducation Level\r\nMarital Status\r\nOccupation\r\nEthnicity\r\n\r\nHere\'s a good article by inc.com about <a href="http://www.inc.com/news/articles/2009/12/customer-demographics.html" target="_blank">why demographics are crucial to your business</a>.\r\n<h3><span style="color: #000000;">Know where your competitors are</span></h3>\r\nKnowing where your competitors operate will give valuable insight into locations you should or should not be. If you\'re a retailer and there are lots of competitors in a specific area, potential could still exist and an opportunity for market entry could still be viable. However if competitors are over saturated, you could be in some trouble. That’s obvious, the hard part is understanding where your competitors are or aren\'t already, and then assessing the available potential. Software solutions like Enterprise have helped companies do this work internally to save time and consultancy costs.\r\n<h3>Understand your market potential</h3>\r\nWhen your target market is clear and you know where your competitors are, you\'ll be able to do some analysis of that information. Some of the things you need to ask yourself when doing analysis are:\r\n\r\nAre there enough people in a particular area that fit my criteria?\r\nDo I understand what drives my target to make decisions?\r\nCan they really afford my products and services?\r\nIs my target accessible, in terms of transportation?\r\nHow difficult or costly will it be to maintain my business in this area?\r\n\r\nAsking these types of questions will help to further identify areas of potential for opening new sites/stores.\r\n\r\nUsing mapping software like <a title="getchee enterprise" href="http://www.getchee.com/solutions/enterprise-index.html">getchee Enterprise</a> can assist companies in self-analyzing market potential in addition to doing in-depth location research before making costly development decision in new locations.\r\n\r\nUltimately, the effectiveness level of location research and planning can make or break a company planning to enter China, or any emerging market country, so must be given high priority and attention. Using the right preparation tools available will make sure your company sets off on the right foot when and if they decided to take the plunge.\r\n<h3>Stay tuned for part 5 of <em>Bringing Your Brand to China: Taking the Plunge</em></h3>', 'Bringing Your Brand to China - Part 4', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'bringing-your-brand-to-china-part-4', '', '\nhttp://blog.getchee.com/?p=2673', '2013-02-20 03:23:50', '2013-02-20 07:23:50', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=3120', 0, 'post', '', 1, ''); 
