Intellectual property rights are important to consider when entering China. The estimated value of some intellectual property (IP) assets can range into the billions of dollars, not an amount to take lightly. For example, the Tropicana trademark, an intellectual asset, is valued at more than U.S. $1 billion, and Marlboro’s trademark is worth up to U.S. $40 billion. That\'s a lot of value on the line. While your trademark might not be worth billions yet, it could be some day, and the steps you take to protect it now will have a lasting effect in the future.\r\n\r\nDevelopment of brand ownership and intellectual property rights in China has seen a lot of changes in the last three decades. While counterfeiting and piracy are still common, especially outside of top-tier cities, new laws offer legal protections similar to what you would find in any western country.\r\n\r\nIn the early 80\'s when China was first re-opening its doors to the west, IP rights were hard to enforce, as they were seen as only benefiting foreign investors and corporations. At that time local economies often depended solely on the revenue streams these industries produced, so resistance was formidable. It\'s also worth noting that China’s traditional legal system originates from Confucian philosophy. Laws were established under these philosophies to protect the interests of the state but without consideration from the people. This philosophy encourages learning through copying, which isn\'t always seen as stealing in China, instead it\'s viewed more as a form of flattery.\r\n\r\nThe 1990\'s saw a wave of new IP protection laws put into place in an effort, not only to attract new investment, but as a way to encourage innovation from within the country as well. Since then the country has seen real change, with the Chinese courts dealing with tens of thousands of IP cases, with many very high profile counterfeiting litigation successes by brands such as Starbucks, Yamaha, Honda, and Coca-cola. Chinese companies have benefited from the reform as well as they grow competitiveness and emerge as high value brands themselves. Avoiding China purely based on fears of piracy should be a thing of the past.\r\n\r\nBrands entering China concerned about IP rights and brand ownership should consider the following tactics:\r\n<h2><strong>1. Register your brand as early as possible</strong></h2>\r\nChina\'s trademark registration system is run on a first-come-first-serve basis, meaning it doesn\'t matter how long you used or if you came up with the idea a long time ago, if you didn\'t register it, it wasn\'t yours to claim. Early registration of your brand names, logos and business is crucial, and should be done even if your business hasn\'t entered China yet.\r\n<h2><strong>2. Don\'t just register in the mainland</strong></h2>\r\nHong Kong and Macao have slightly different IP laws; therefore your brand needs to be registered separately in those areas. Overlooking this could have negative consequences in your future.\r\n<h2><strong>3. Register in Chinese too</strong></h2>\r\nWhile English literacy is on the rise, most people in China still only speak and write in Chinese, and could find it hard to pronounce and recognize your logos and trademarks if they are in another language. All brands should have Chinese counterparts, which should be registered as well. If you don\'t, they might just develop their own version of your mark, and there\'s no guarantee you\'ll like what they come up with for you. Take the initiative and make sure your Chinese versions are something the company can stand behind. But do your research. Don\'t just Google translate your English name into Chinese; it might not mean what you want it to. Find someone who knows the culture and the language to help your company present itself in a way that’s both proper for the company AND the culture. You\'ll save face and gain more respect from your Chinese customers.\r\n<h2><strong>4. Monitor frequently</strong></h2>\r\nIt’s easy to monitor your brand online with free online trademark registries and other tools for identifying cyber-squatters and other brand offenders, so brand owners should use them regularly. Companies with large networks could even consider employing a brand monitoring team. If you don\'t monitor, you won\'t know who\'s doing what with your brand name and how it could affect your company.\r\n<h2><strong>5. Educate employees</strong></h2>\r\nYour workforce should know about and be able to understand the value or your brand, and see it as something worth protecting. Since brand value awareness is still relatively low in China, these values should be thoroughly explained to all employees in an effort to recruit them as your brand ambassadors. If people don\'t value your brand on the inside, what can you expect on the outside?\r\n<h2><strong>6. Consider place of jurisdiction</strong></h2>\r\nIf you\'re providing licenses for third parties to use your product or brand in China you should include a clause in the license agreement that provides for disputes to be dealt with in an alternative jurisdiction.\r\n\r\nHong Kong might be the best choice: its court process is faster and more efficient than China\'s. You should also be thinking about in-country enforcement measures. What can or can\'t be done if you do have a dispute?\r\n<h2><strong>7. Use enforcement procedures</strong></h2>\r\nIf a brand infringement is found in China, there are efficient means available for a business to enforce its IP rights. There are two principal routes for enforcement: administrative and judicial.\r\n\r\nThe administrative route will normally be the first option as brand owners can enforce their rights without needing to go to court. It’s cheaper and quicker. If found guilty, the violator can be fined and money earned from the infringement can be seized. The disadvantage of this process is that damages are not available for the brand owner. The judicial route is more similar to a Western system where the brand owner sues the infringing party in court and remedies include damages and injunctions. This option can be unpredictable though, as brands risk a long drawn out process and adverse publicity.\r\n\r\nBy taking the right steps to protect your brand and intellectual property rights before you get to China, you\'ll be in a much better position when you decide to take the plunge.\r\n<h3><strong>Stay tuned for part 4 of <a href="http://blog.getchee.com/?p=3120"><em>Bringing Your Brand to China: Deciding on Locations</em></a>\r\n</strong></h3>', 'Bringing Your Brand to China - Part 3', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'bring-your-brand-to-china-part-3', '', '', '2013-02-20 03:23:50', '2013-02-20 07:23:50', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=3057', 0, 'post', '', 1, ''); 
Staff Development - Super City\r\nProduct Presentation and Social Media - <a href="http://www.bata.com/" target="_blank">Bata Shoes</a>\r\nLandlord Communications - Combi\r\n<blockquote>One of the key take-aways for me was that there is a wealth of retail  experience in the China market, but still very under-developed channels for  learning and sharing skills and experience</blockquote>\r\n<cite>Philip Tomlin, getchee</cite>\r\n\r\nAs it did with its Shanghai event in April, getchee hopes it can continue to play a key role in the future fostering of more channels for knowledge sharing and networking.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://events.getchee.com/all-events.html" target="_blank">Watch a recap of the event "Tools and Processes for Store Network Success in China"</a>\r\n\r\nOur own James Grigsby shared a range of tools and approaches that retailers can use to assess market size, prioritize cities, identify and rank trade zones, and choose winning locations.\r\n\r\n"Although solutions exist for many different business functions, they are very immature or non-existent for store development -- which seems odd considering how important location is to retailers." - James Grigsby\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.getchee.com/services/services-index.html" target="_blank">Learn more</a> about getchee services and what they can do for you business.', 'Marcus Evans Presents Wealth of Retail Experience in China', 0, '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'markus-evens-event', '', '', '2013-02-20 03:23:50', '2013-02-20 07:23:50', '', 0, 'http://blog.getchee.com/?p=3090', 0, 'post', '', 0, ''); 
